00:00:21.037 --> 00:00:22.870
DENIS GOROKHOV: So I
work at Morgan Stanley.

00:00:22.870 --> 00:00:27.630
I run corporate treasury
strategies at Morgan Stanley.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:29.580
So corporate treasury
is the business unit

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:32.195
that is responsible for
issuing and risk management

00:00:32.195 --> 00:00:35.500
of Morgan Stanley debt.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:39.770
I also run desk strategies own
the New York inflation desk.

00:00:39.770 --> 00:00:43.100
That's the business which is
a part of the global interest

00:00:43.100 --> 00:00:47.970
rate business, which is
responsible for trading

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:49.870
derivatives linked to inflation.

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:53.560
And today, I'm going to
talk about the HJM model.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:59.600
So HJM model-- the abbreviation
stands for Heath-Jarrow-Morton,

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:03.730
these three individuals who
discovered this framework

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:05.620
in the beginning of 1990s.

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.580
And this is a very
general framework

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:13.180
for pricing derivatives to
interest rates and to credit.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:18.290
So on Wall Street, big banks
make a substantial amount

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:21.090
of money by trading all
kinds of exotic products,

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:22.190
exotic derivatives.

00:01:22.190 --> 00:01:26.130
And big banks like
Morgan Stanley,

00:01:26.130 --> 00:01:31.130
like Goldman, JP Morgan--
trades thousands and thousands

00:01:31.130 --> 00:01:33.670
of different types of
exotic derivatives.

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:40.440
So a typical problem
which the business faces

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.570
is that new types of
derivatives arrive all the time.

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:47.470
So you need to be able
to respond quickly

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:50.030
to the demand from the clients.

00:01:50.030 --> 00:01:52.360
And you need to be
able not just to tell

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:53.700
the price of derivative.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:59.240
You need to be able also to
risk manage this derivative.

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:01.280
Because let's say if
you sold an option,

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:03.090
you've got some
premium, if something

00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:05.990
goes not in your favor,
you need to pay in the end.

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:09.550
So you need to be able to hedge.

00:02:09.550 --> 00:02:13.590
And you can think
about the HJM model,

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:16.890
like this kind of
framework, as something

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:19.590
which is similar to theoretical
physics in a way, right?

00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:26.000
So you get beautiful models--
it's like a solvable model.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.600
For example, let's
say the hydrogen atom

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:32.430
in quantum mechanics.

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:34.890
So it's relatively
straightforward to solve it,

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:35.660
right?

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:39.810
So we have an equation,
which can be exactly solved.

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:42.975
And we can find energy
levels and understand this

00:02:42.975 --> 00:02:43.600
fairly quickly.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.330
But if you start going into more
complex problems-- for example,

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:49.970
you add one more
electron and you

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:53.090
have a helium atom-- it's
already much more complicated.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.170
And then if you have complicated
atoms or even molecules,

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:57.620
it's unclear what to do.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.540
So people came up
with approximate kind

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:06.150
of methods, which allow
nevertheless solve everything

00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:09.070
very accurately numerically.

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:11.400
And HJM is a similar framework.

00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:16.050
So you can-- it allows
to price all kinds

00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:17.920
of [INAUDIBLE] derivatives.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:26.150
And so it's very general.

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:28.450
It's very flexible to
incorporate new payoffs,

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:32.010
all kinds of correlation between
products and so on, so forth.

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:38.130
And this HJM model--
[INAUDIBLE] natural [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:41.830
more general framework like
Monte Carlo simulation.

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:46.135
And before actually
going into details

00:03:46.135 --> 00:03:49.610
of pricing exotic interest
rates and credit derivatives,

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:52.190
let me just first explain
how this framework appears

00:03:52.190 --> 00:03:55.420
in the most common type
of derivatives, basically

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:57.400
equity-linked product.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:59.610
So like a very, very
simple example, right?

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:04.580
So let's say if we have a
derivatives desk at some firm,

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:06.680
and they sell all
kinds of products.

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:08.720
Of course, ideally,
let's say there's

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:10.740
a client who wants to
buy something from you.

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:13.480
Of course, the easiest approach
would be to find the client

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:20.790
and do an opposite transaction
with him, so that you're market

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:22.695
neutral, at least in theory.

00:04:22.695 --> 00:04:24.070
So if you don't
take into account

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:25.290
counterparties and so on.

00:04:25.290 --> 00:04:27.740
However, it's rather
difficult in general,

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.590
so the portfolios
are very complicated.

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:33.170
And there's always
some residual risk.

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:35.700
So this is the cause
of dynamic hedging.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:38.660
So for this example,
very simple example,

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:42.350
a dealer just sold a
call option on a stock.

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:44.800
And if you do this,
then in principle,

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.050
the amount of money which
you can lose is unlimited.

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:53.010
So you need to be able
to hedge dynamically

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:56.980
by trading underlying,
for example, in this case.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:02.460
So just a brief
illustration of the stock

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:14.110
markets, you see how random it
has been for the last 20 years

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:14.800
or so.

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:20.150
So first of all, this
year, some kind of--

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:23.790
from beginnings of the
1990s to around 2000,

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:25.500
we see really very
sharp increase.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:28.950
And then we have dot-com
bubble, and then we

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:32.470
have the bank
[INAUDIBLE] of 2008.

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:35.820
And if you trade derivatives
whose payoff depends,

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.476
for example, on
the FTSE 100 index,

00:05:38.476 --> 00:05:39.600
you should be very careful.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:40.100
All right?

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:43.250
Because market can drop,
and you need to be hedged.

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:49.370
So you need to be able to come
with some kind of good models

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:51.380
which can recalibrate
to the markets

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:59.920
and which can truly risk
manage your position.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:06.970
So the so the general idea
of pricing derivatives

00:06:06.970 --> 00:06:14.460
is that one starts from
some stochastic process.

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:23.240
So in this example here, it's
probably like the simplest

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:26.140
possible-- nevertheless a
very instructive-- model,

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:30.050
which is essentially like
these [INAUDIBLE] Black-Scholes

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:39.710
