first approximation

00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:43.150
for the actual dynamics.

00:07:43.150 --> 00:07:46.180
So in this example, we have
stochastic differential

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:50.300
equation for the stock price.

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:55.390
And it consists-- it's
the sum of two terms.

00:07:55.390 --> 00:08:00.040
This is a drift, it's some
kind of deterministic part

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:02.380
of the stock price dynamics.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:04.750
And here, also,
we have diffusion.

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:10.940
So here, dB is the Brownian
motion driving the stock,

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:13.540
and S is the price
of the stock here.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:15.780
Mu is the drift.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:19.710
And sigma is the
volatility of the stock.

00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:23.660
Particularly, it
shows the randomness.

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:28.050
And it's the randomness
impact on the stock price.

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:37.539
And using this model, one
can derive the Black-Scholes

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:38.090
formula.

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:40.510
And the Black-Scholes
formula shows

00:08:40.510 --> 00:08:47.990
how to price derivatives
whose payoff depends

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:51.950
on the price of the stock.

00:08:51.950 --> 00:08:56.420
So here, if you look at
this differential equation,

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:57.840
then you can answer
the question.

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:02.260
Let's say if you started
from some initial value

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:04.290
for the stock at time t.

00:09:04.290 --> 00:09:11.440
And then we started the clock.

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:15.730
Which are now to be
at time capital T.

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:21.167
And given that time T,
then stock price is S_T.

00:09:21.167 --> 00:09:22.750
So what's the
probability distribution

00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:26.200
for the stock at time T?

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:33.820
So this kind of equation
can be very easily solved.

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:42.130
And one can obtain analytically
the probability distribution

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:44.530
function at any
[INAUDIBLE] moment of time.

00:09:44.530 --> 00:09:48.010
So I mean, I just think
I'll write a few equations,

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:50.180
because it's very important
to understand this.

00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:54.650
So I'm sure you probably
have seen something like this

00:09:54.650 --> 00:09:59.630
already, but let me just
show you the main ideas

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:01.280
beyond this formula.

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:06.060
So if you have a
random process--

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:10.200
let's say A is some process,
stochastic process, which

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:10.890
is normal.

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:13.290
So it follows some drift.

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:18.831
Plus some volatility term.

00:10:18.831 --> 00:10:19.330
Right?

00:10:19.330 --> 00:10:21.610
So the difference
between this equation

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:24.370
is that I don't multiply
by A here and A here.

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:31.330
Especially, it's much
simpler to solve.

00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:32.720
So the solution
for this equation

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:33.930
is very straightforward.

00:10:33.930 --> 00:10:39.604
So at any moment of time T,
if you start at moment 0,

00:10:39.604 --> 00:10:42.020
the solution of the equation
would be something like this.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:42.603
Drift-- right?

00:10:42.603 --> 00:10:44.150
I'm simply integrating.

00:10:44.150 --> 00:10:51.450
Plus-- and I assume that B of
t is standard Brownian motion,

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:54.950
so at time 0, it's 0.

00:10:54.950 --> 00:11:01.680
And then it's very
easy to see now that...

00:11:08.550 --> 00:11:11.690
is equal to the Brownian motion.

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:14.100
But this is nothing else.

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:21.420
It's some random number,
which is normally distributed,

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:23.280
times square root of time.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:25.561
So epsilon is
proportional to it.

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:32.570
OK, so basically, this
means that this is normally

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:33.750
distributed.

00:11:33.750 --> 00:11:41.730
And its-- and probability
distribution for this quantity

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:44.240
is equal to-- we know
it's exactly, right,

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:46.975
because this is like a
standard Gaussian distribution.

00:11:50.900 --> 00:11:58.410
And if you simply
substitute A into here,

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:02.520
then you will obtain the
probability distribution

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:05.260
for the actual quantity.

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:08.420
And I'll just write it
for the completeness.

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:16.770
So basically, we obtain
probability distribution

00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:25.020
for the standard variable.

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:26.390
So this is straightforward.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:29.910
So the only difference between
the case I'm doing here

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:33.100
is that the dynamics is
assumed to be log-normal.

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:33.600
Right?

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:35.660
And the interpretation
is very simple.

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:38.190
If it's normal, then
the price of the stock

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:39.912
can become negative.

00:12:39.912 --> 00:12:41.370
Which is just a
financial nonsense.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:43.470
So the [INAUDIBLE]
log-normal dynamics basically

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:48.570
is a good first approximation.

00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:51.040
And in this case, what
helps as a result is just

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:52.740
known as Ito's lemma.

00:12:52.740 --> 00:12:54.595
So I just first of all
write it, and then I

00:12:54.595 --> 00:12:57.590
will explain how
you can obtain it.

00:12:57.590 --> 00:13:01.590
And if you look
at this equation--

00:13:01.590 --> 00:13:07.030
