00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:56.660
So this is all
very clear, right?

00:16:56.660 --> 00:16:59.250
This is standard calculus?

00:16:59.250 --> 00:17:00.960
It's straightforward.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:04.450
But there is an additional term
that looks a bit suspicious.

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:06.990
And I will explain
what it actually

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:08.550
means on the next slide.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:12.640
So a very important thing is
that when you calculate dC,

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:15.310
then you will obtain
deterministic term which

00:17:15.310 --> 00:17:17.869
is proportional to
the second derivative.

00:17:17.869 --> 00:17:21.416
And you see, there is no-- the
fact is that you have here dt,

00:17:21.416 --> 00:17:23.790
basically this looks like it's
an additional contribution

00:17:23.790 --> 00:17:25.869
to the drift.

00:17:25.869 --> 00:17:27.750
We view this as drift,
and this is a drift.

00:17:27.750 --> 00:17:29.937
And there is no, any
more, stochasticity.

00:17:29.937 --> 00:17:30.770
It's very important.

00:17:30.770 --> 00:17:32.980
This is like a crucial fact
beyond the Black-Scholes

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:38.030
formalism and the Monte
Carlo method in finance.

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:41.090
And then, the idea, you
can read, for example,

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:42.990
in Hull's book,
its standard proof.

00:17:42.990 --> 00:17:53.050
So if we issue an option,
then we hedge it--

00:17:53.050 --> 00:17:57.090
by having a certain
position in the underlying.

00:17:57.090 --> 00:18:00.370
So the idea is like this.

00:18:00.370 --> 00:18:02.860
Let's say I sold a call
option of the stock.

00:18:02.860 --> 00:18:05.500
So when the stock market
goes, up I make some money.

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:07.820
And then, in the same
time, I short the stock,

00:18:07.820 --> 00:18:09.520
so I lose money on my hedge.

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:14.290
And wherever the market goes,
I don't make or lose money.

00:18:14.290 --> 00:18:18.750
So that's the idea,
basically, beyond hedging.

00:18:18.750 --> 00:18:23.830
And basically, what
happens if I calculate

00:18:23.830 --> 00:18:27.990
the change in my
portfolio, then since there

00:18:27.990 --> 00:18:31.380
is no risk involved, I
assume I am perfectly hedged.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:36.420
Then I simply obtain
the risk-free return.

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:39.820
So r here is the
risk-free interest rate.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:48.450
So if you simply
look at this equation

00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:51.150
and substitute the
Ito's lemma result here,

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:53.830
then you obtain like a
very simple equation,

00:18:53.830 --> 00:18:55.710
which is basically
Black-Scholes differential

00:18:55.710 --> 00:19:00.490
equation for the stock--
for the price of the option.

00:19:00.490 --> 00:19:03.650
So this equation is
very fundamental.

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:07.160
And it's very elegant.

00:19:07.160 --> 00:19:12.790
So you can see although
originally, right,

00:19:12.790 --> 00:19:17.986
if you started from something
with some arbitrary risk,

00:19:17.986 --> 00:19:20.190
with some arbitrary drift mu.

00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:20.690
Right?

00:19:20.690 --> 00:19:22.440
Which is basically--
it could be anything.

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:28.370
Which is that this drift mu
drops out of the equation.

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:33.120
And it depends on
the interest rate.

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:35.350
And this is a very
interesting fact.

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:49.040
So and this very interesting
fact has to do with hedging.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:50.910
Again, you have
position in an option,

00:19:50.910 --> 00:19:53.610
and you have an opposite
position in underlying.

00:19:53.610 --> 00:19:57.350
And that's how the
drift disappears.

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:00.710
If you look at the movement
of both the positions,

00:20:00.710 --> 00:20:04.670
then you see that there that
the drift will disappear.

00:20:04.670 --> 00:20:08.500
So it's a very important
and striking fact.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:14.700
And the second thing,
which is truly a miracle,

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:17.670
is that risk is
eliminated completely.

00:20:17.670 --> 00:20:21.170
So this equation has
absolutely no stochasticity.

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:22.410
So you can just solve it.

00:20:22.410 --> 00:20:25.290
If you specify
the option payoff,

00:20:25.290 --> 00:20:27.630
and if you know your
volatility, which

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:33.480
is a measure of your-- basically
often how the stock fluctuates.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:35.700
And if you know the
risk-free interest rate,

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:38.000
you can just price the options.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.750
And this is a true
miracle that occurs.

00:20:40.750 --> 00:20:43.180
And when I was studying
this, I couldn't really

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:44.890
understand this--
maybe because I

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:46.600
was coming from
theoretical physics,

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:51.690
and all this result called
Ito's lemma is buried somewhere

00:20:51.690 --> 00:20:55.605
in stochastic calculus.

00:20:55.605 --> 00:20:57.855
And I would just try to
understand in [INAUDIBLE] what

00:20:57.855 --> 00:20:59.070
it all means.

00:20:59.070 --> 00:21:01.890
And let them just
explain here, basically

00:21:01.890 --> 00:21:06.920
how one can understand
this result, Ito's lemma,

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:08.941
in a very simple term.

00:21:08.941 --> 00:21:09.690
[INAUDIBLE] terms.

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:12.370
So let me just write--
let me remind you.

00:21:12.370 --> 00:21:15.220
So Ito's lemma basically tells
the following-- once again,

00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:19.040
so if C is the function
of stochastic variables,

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:23.360
of stochastic variable
S, then its differential

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:27.060
is not just equal to some
standard result from calculus.

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:33.890
But we also get some kind
of very exotic term, which

00:21:33.890 --> 00:21:39.770
is basically very nontrivial.

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:43.050
And let me just try to explain
to you how actually it appears.

00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:45.900
So just to understand
this, I recommend everybody

00:21:45.900 --> 00:21:47.760
after this lecture,
look at this derivation,

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:51.510
because it really explains
what this Ito's lemma means.

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:53.710
So the idea is very simple.

00:21:53.710 --> 00:21:58.560
So let's start from electrons
for the first principles.

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:01.765
And let's say we have
an interval of time,

00:22:01.765 --> 00:22:03.330
with length dt.

00:22:03.330 --> 00:22:06.240
And let's say we divide
it into n intervals,

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:10.522
and each interval
length is dt prime.

00:22:10.522 --> 00:22:11.750
Right?

00:22:11.750 --> 00:22:17.410
And I assume that the
ratio of dt over dt prime

00:22:17.410 --> 00:22:19.240
is sufficiently large.

00:22:21.870 --> 00:22:26.310
So first, we know that
our stock, as we know,

00:22:26.310 --> 00:22:29.290
follows the log-normal dynamics.

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:39.010
So this means that if I go from
from time i to time i plus 1,

00:22:39.010 --> 00:22:43.010
here you need to
exchange i and i minus 1.

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:45.881
So then, you can always
[INAUDIBLE] the following form,

00:22:45.881 --> 00:22:46.380
right?

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.660
So S at time i plus
1 minus S at time i

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:56.004
is equal to the
drift term-- right?

00:22:56.004 --> 00:22:58.420
Which is a discrete version
of the stochastic differential

00:22:58.420 --> 00:22:59.230
equation.

00:22:59.230 --> 00:23:00.840
Plus the randomness.

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:03.630
So here again,
sigma is volatility.

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:05.880
It's the measure of how
the stock fluctuates,

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:09.070
which is the stock price,
which is square root of dt,

00:23:09.070 --> 00:23:11.780
because Brownian
motion fluctuation is

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:13.530
proportional to the time.

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:18.990
And also here, we have
epsilon, and epsilon

00:23:18.990 --> 00:23:21.680
is a standard normal variable.

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:23.630
Then-- OK, so we have this.

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:25.440
This is pretty straightforward.

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:27.730
Basically, I just throw
stochastic differential

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:29.010
equation on the latest.

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:32.850
And I go from point
i to point i plus 1.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:41.750
Now, let's see what it means
for the price of the option.

00:23:41.750 --> 00:23:46.140
So again, so C is the
price of the option.

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:53.580
At time T, when the stock
price is equal to S_(i+1).

00:23:53.580 --> 00:23:57.060
So the change in
the option price

00:23:57.060 --> 00:23:59.110
is equal to-- like
the first term, just

00:23:59.110 --> 00:24:01.450
something very standard,
standard calculus.

00:24:01.450 --> 00:24:07.260
Plus the first derivatives and
the difference in the stock

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:10.260
price, plus I take
the second-order term,

00:24:10.260 --> 00:24:12.890
this is the second
derivative, and I

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:18.840
have here S times i plus
1, minus S times i squared.

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:21.950
So this is approximate, because
I'm taking only the main terms.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:25.410
Or the other terms, given that
both times dt and dt prime

00:24:25.410 --> 00:24:27.600
are very small, they
can be neglected.

00:24:27.600 --> 00:24:30.640
So you can check it carefully
at home if you want to.

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:36.100
But I guarantee that
there is no miracle here.

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:37.720
Everything we need is here.

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:42.150
Now let's do the following.

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:43.274
So we have this equation.

00:24:43.274 --> 00:24:44.440
And let's look at this term.

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:47.780
So this term, basically, is the
cornerstone of the Ito's lemma.

00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:53.940
So let's take this
equation for the difference

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:56.270
and substitute into here.

00:24:56.270 --> 00:24:59.860
And you see here, again, you
can look-- what is important,

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:01.100
against the time scales.

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:03.950
So dt prime is very small.

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:09.841
Therefore, the term, which
is random, dominates here.

00:25:09.841 --> 00:25:10.340
Right?

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:11.923
Because [INAUDIBLE]
square root of dt.

00:25:11.923 --> 00:25:15.220
And square root for small
times is much bigger

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:17.070
than the linear function.

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:22.250
Therefore, we simply neglect
this term compared this term.

00:25:22.250 --> 00:25:27.480
And with linear
accuracy in dt prime,

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:31.760
we can approximate
this just by this term.

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:36.800
Now, what to do-- so again,
we wrote the same equation,

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:40.100
that latest difference
for the option price

00:25:40.100 --> 00:25:41.980
of two neighboring points.

00:25:41.980 --> 00:25:44.400
And what I'm doing right now,
I have all this equation,

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:48.560
and I will simply sum them--
basically from 0 to N.

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:53.010
So let's say I have all these
equations from 0 to N minus 1,

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:54.630
and I sum them.

00:25:54.630 --> 00:25:56.340
And again, it's
very straightforward

00:25:56.340 --> 00:25:58.610
and obtains the full equation.

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:03.160
And again, what is very
interesting is that we will

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:05.600
obtain-- you look at this term.

00:26:05.600 --> 00:26:09.290
So this term is
very complicated.

00:26:09.290 --> 00:26:10.780
It's essentially
stochastic right?

00:26:10.780 --> 00:26:13.390
Because-- it looks
like very stochastic.

00:26:13.390 --> 00:26:16.250
And because--
remember that this is

00:26:16.250 --> 00:26:18.000
the standard normal variable.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.890
And all of them are independent.

00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:26.030
So in principle, we
have the sum of N

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:28.630
independent normal
variables squared.

00:26:28.630 --> 00:26:33.570
And it turns out-- it's really
a very beautiful result,

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:37.050
and I recommend everybody
also do it at home,

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:39.180
I try to show you right
now on the blackboard--

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:43.130
that if you sum up all
this epsilon squared,

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:46.550
that in the limit when
N goes to infinity,

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:50.960
this term becomes deterministic.

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:55.900
So let me just
show you basically

00:26:55.900 --> 00:26:58.180
what exactly is meant.

00:26:58.180 --> 00:27:04.930
So what I mean by deterministic
is that of course,

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:14.890
if I have epsilon squared,
then it's-- there is some

00:27:14.890 --> 00:27:16.440
probability distribution, right?

00:27:16.440 --> 00:27:21.250
It's distributed between
0 and infinity, right?

00:27:21.250 --> 00:27:23.270
So this is some
kind of function.

00:27:23.270 --> 00:27:29.500
But my claim is
that once I start

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:37.220
adding more and more numbers--
and so on, and so on-- then

00:27:37.220 --> 00:27:42.170
this function will become
more and more and more narrow.

00:27:42.170 --> 00:27:46.060
So it behaves like a
deterministic random--

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:50.430
like a completely deterministic
variable in the large N limit.

00:27:50.430 --> 00:27:55.850
And to do this, let me
just write a very simple--

00:27:55.850 --> 00:27:57.260
write explicitly of what I mean.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:04.521
So essentially, remember that
we have the sum of variables.

00:28:04.521 --> 00:28:05.020
Right?

00:28:10.570 --> 00:28:16.010
And for us to show that
it's become deterministic,

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:19.830
we need to show
that it squared--

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:33.790
The width of the distribution,
which I defined as-- let's say

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:35.170
you have a variable, right?

00:28:35.170 --> 00:28:40.340
And if I defined the dispersion
in the following way,

00:28:40.340 --> 00:28:44.730
now I define here the dispersion
for this random variable which

00:28:44.730 --> 00:28:47.695
is equal to the sum
of epsilon squared.

00:28:47.695 --> 00:29:00.080
So if I write it here,
then it turns out

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:05.210
that each term in
this equation is

00:29:05.210 --> 00:29:09.520
proportional to N
squared, which is natural.

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:12.870
But it turns out that the
difference in the large N limit

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:17.220
is proportional only
to N. Therefore,

00:29:17.220 --> 00:29:23.640
if you have this variable,
which-- if you sum up

00:29:23.640 --> 00:29:27.180
more and more terms, then
we'll have a variable.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:30.470
We have a distribution
for this variable, which

00:29:30.470 --> 00:29:32.080
is moving in this direction.

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:35.280
And of course it
moves this direction,

00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:39.960
but it becomes more and more
and more narrow, basically.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:42.910
So as the limit of
N tends to infinity,

00:29:42.910 --> 00:29:51.200
it becomes a deterministic.

00:29:51.200 --> 00:29:53.370
So I'd recommend
everybody at home just do

00:29:53.370 --> 00:29:54.960
this very simple exercise.

00:29:54.960 --> 00:30:05.840
And you will see that
essentially, the sum behaves

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:09.000
as a deterministic quantity.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:20.740
So just to do this,
you need to you

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:25.330
need to know the very
simple properties

00:30:25.330 --> 00:30:28.190
of the standard
normal distribution.

00:30:28.190 --> 00:30:31.970
First of all, the average
expected value of epsilon

00:30:31.970 --> 00:30:33.970
is equal to 1, right?

00:30:33.970 --> 00:30:35.380
For a standard normal variable.

00:30:35.380 --> 00:30:37.650
And also, you need to know
that the fourth moment

00:30:37.650 --> 00:30:42.050
of the normal variable
is equal to 3.

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.710
So if you have this, then
you can calculate this,

00:30:45.710 --> 00:30:47.590
which is trivial to calculate.

00:30:47.590 --> 00:30:55.217
And then you can come to this
property that, once again,

00:30:55.217 --> 00:30:57.550
probability distribution
function, in the large N limit,

00:30:57.550 --> 00:30:58.760
behaves deterministic.

00:30:58.760 --> 00:31:01.270
It essentially becomes
like a delta function.

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:04.025
So this is a very
interesting result,

00:31:04.025 --> 00:31:09.460
because it basically explains
why in the Black-Scholes

00:31:09.460 --> 00:31:15.950
equation, we have this very
weird by deterministic term.

00:31:15.950 --> 00:31:21.170
And that's why the option
pricing is possible.

00:31:21.170 --> 00:31:23.520
Because if you started
pricing options--

00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:25.870
like if you don't know
anything about Black-Scholes,

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:28.780
it might be that there's
no price for the option,

00:31:28.780 --> 00:31:31.630
because it might be that
although you do hedge,

00:31:31.630 --> 00:31:34.420
you still cannot eliminate
your randomness completely.

00:31:34.420 --> 00:31:40.570
Maybe hedge helps you with just
too narrow the distribution

00:31:40.570 --> 00:31:44.150
of your outcome, but we're
just not guaranteed at all.

00:31:44.150 --> 00:31:51.167
So it's really very-- Ito's
Lemma, which is usually

00:31:51.167 --> 00:31:52.750
in every book on
derivatives, probably

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:58.210
like the first
equation ever written,

00:31:58.210 --> 00:31:59.890
basically is given
without any proof.

00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:04.710
But this-- in reality, it's
a very interesting limit.

00:32:04.710 --> 00:32:12.530
So it can be realized only if
you have two different time

00:32:12.530 --> 00:32:13.300
scales.

00:32:13.300 --> 00:32:16.070
So the small time
scale, which is dt prime

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:19.410
is-- in the business
sense, it corresponds

00:32:19.410 --> 00:32:21.180
to your hedging frequency.

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:24.150
It's when you rebalance
your hedging portfolio.

00:32:24.150 --> 00:32:28.110
And the time dt, there's
a time scale dt, which

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:30.710
is much bigger than dt prime.

00:32:30.710 --> 00:32:35.210
It's at the time at which
you look at your portfolio.

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:40.390
So only in this very weird
limit, when dt over dt prime

00:32:40.390 --> 00:32:44.190
goes to infinity, you
strictly have Ito's Lemma.

00:32:44.190 --> 00:32:46.805
So actually, if you look
even like is most famous book

00:32:46.805 --> 00:32:48.050
on derivatives.

00:32:48.050 --> 00:32:51.510
If you look at this edition,
you will see actually

00:32:51.510 --> 00:32:54.540
that the proof
actually isn't correct.

00:32:54.540 --> 00:32:58.720
So just look at it and
find what's wrong there.

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:00.670
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] normal?

00:33:00.670 --> 00:33:03.265
DENIS GOROKHOV: Sorry?

00:33:03.265 --> 00:33:04.610
AUDIENCE: That's what it is?

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:07.160
DENIS GOROKHOV: Yeah, this
is what [INAUDIBLE] means.

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:09.350
So if you use these
two results here,

00:33:09.350 --> 00:33:17.630
you will see that your
it's proportional only

00:33:17.630 --> 00:33:19.480
to N, not to N squared.

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:27.280
So that's why your distribution
becomes more and more narrow.

00:33:27.280 --> 00:33:31.950
Because when you sum
up, what it means

00:33:31.950 --> 00:33:35.404
is you sum up more
and more variables.

00:33:35.404 --> 00:33:37.320
Each of them was like
random normal variables.

00:33:37.320 --> 00:33:40.650
So the average--
average goes like N.

00:33:40.650 --> 00:33:44.110
But the dispersion--
the dispersion, right?

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.540
That's the standard
deviation, right?

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:49.640
You have a square
root of N. That's

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:53.130
why basically, square
root of N over N is small.

00:33:53.130 --> 00:33:56.190
So by increasing
N, basically you

00:33:56.190 --> 00:34:03.100
become more and more
and more deterministic.

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:06.541
So that's the main fact
beyond Ito's lemma.

00:34:06.541 --> 00:34:07.540
So that's it's obtained.

00:34:07.540 --> 00:34:09.956
So I recommend everybody just
look in detail, because this

00:34:09.956 --> 00:34:12.590
is the cornerstone of
derivatives pricing theory,

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:15.795
but at many books it's
not really well-written.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:23.370
So when I was studying,
it was like I couldn't

00:34:23.370 --> 00:34:24.510
understand for a while.

00:34:24.510 --> 00:34:26.989
So it took me a time
just to understand.

00:34:26.989 --> 00:34:27.730
What else?

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:30.219
And a very interesting
thing now is

00:34:30.219 --> 00:34:32.650
that remember that
we used Ito's lemma--

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:36.620
and basically, we are able
to obtain this equation.

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:46.120
And this equation is very
well known in literature.

00:34:46.120 --> 00:34:47.860
It's very similar to
the heat equation.

00:34:47.860 --> 00:34:51.929
And heat equation can be
solved using standard methods.

00:34:51.929 --> 00:34:55.467
And I don't want to write
any derivation here,

00:34:55.467 --> 00:34:56.800
it's relatively straightforward.

00:34:56.800 --> 00:34:59.190
Maybe a bit cumbersome
but straightforward.

00:34:59.190 --> 00:35:04.987
And if payoff of your
option at maturity

00:35:04.987 --> 00:35:07.570
is given by some function, which
is not really important here.

00:35:07.570 --> 00:35:09.650
Because you can write a
very general solution.

00:35:12.420 --> 00:35:17.270
So what is here is
essentially Green's function

00:35:17.270 --> 00:35:19.960
of this equation.

00:35:19.960 --> 00:35:24.230
And this Green's function,
if you look at this equation,

00:35:24.230 --> 00:35:29.200
is very similar to the
probability distribution

00:35:29.200 --> 00:35:34.000
function, which we have on this
slide in the very beginning.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:39.500
So this function is
identical to this function,

00:35:39.500 --> 00:35:45.550
and the only difference
is that the drift of stock

00:35:45.550 --> 00:35:47.000
in the real world disappears.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:52.960
And we are left only
with the interest rate.

00:35:52.960 --> 00:36:01.240
And so this equation, which
is again, also very important

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:03.940
for the derivatives
pricing, is how

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:10.050
we come up with the whole idea
of Monte Carlo simulation.

00:36:10.050 --> 00:36:13.490
So this is nothing else as
a Green's function, which

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:17.090
basically tells us
how the stock evolves

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:20.080
in the risk-neutral space.

00:36:20.080 --> 00:36:23.320
Risk-neutral space is
essentially some kind

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:26.610
of imaginary world,
like [INAUDIBLE] world,

00:36:26.610 --> 00:36:39.102
where all the assets' drift is
just the interest rate and not

00:36:39.102 --> 00:36:39.810
the actual drift.

00:36:39.810 --> 00:36:42.230
So it's very fundamental.

00:36:42.230 --> 00:36:45.180
So it's very important things
that the drift in real world

00:36:45.180 --> 00:36:46.732
drops out of all the equations.

00:36:46.732 --> 00:36:49.190
So the only parameter which
actually does matter for option

00:36:49.190 --> 00:36:50.992
pricing is volatility.

00:36:50.992 --> 00:36:53.450
So this parameter's relatively
easier to understand, right?

00:36:53.450 --> 00:36:57.720
Because that's how much money
your deterministic investment

00:36:57.720 --> 00:37:00.900
basically makes.

00:37:00.900 --> 00:37:03.190
So [INAUDIBLE] is the
[INAUDIBLE] parameter.

00:37:03.190 --> 00:37:10.140
So naively, you could
expect I need both mu-- let

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:12.622
me just remind you what mu is.

00:37:12.622 --> 00:37:14.330
Mu and sigma, two
independent parameters.

00:37:14.330 --> 00:37:16.663
But it turns out mu completely
drops out of the picture.

00:37:16.663 --> 00:37:18.390
And this is because
of dynamic hedging,

00:37:18.390 --> 00:37:20.360
because we hedged the position.

00:37:20.360 --> 00:37:26.556
And so now this
equation-- since this

00:37:26.556 --> 00:37:28.680
is basically Green's
function, and Green's function

00:37:28.680 --> 00:37:38.910
tells us what's the
probability density

00:37:38.910 --> 00:37:41.380
of the stock at some
time in the future,

00:37:41.380 --> 00:37:47.890
if the stock were at
some point initially,

00:37:47.890 --> 00:37:56.720
then basically this means
that we can simulate the stock

00:37:56.720 --> 00:37:57.570
dynamics.

00:37:57.570 --> 00:37:59.400
And we can price
derivatives, like,

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:01.020
using a very simple framework.

00:38:01.020 --> 00:38:03.210
So what do we do?

00:38:03.210 --> 00:38:06.540
We simply write the
equation for the stock

00:38:06.540 --> 00:38:09.040
in the risk-neutral world.

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:12.600
Remember, the difference is
that instead of the actual drift

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:17.369
of the stock, mu, we substitute
here by the interest rate.

00:38:17.369 --> 00:38:19.660
And this is basically how
much money, roughly speaking,

00:38:19.660 --> 00:38:21.280
the bank account makes.

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:30.000
And what we do-- we start from
some stock value at time 0,

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:35.432
and then we simulate stock
along different paths.

00:38:35.432 --> 00:38:36.890
So there are like
three paths here.

00:38:36.890 --> 00:38:39.180
There could be like thousands.

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:42.070
So now-- and you
know, now, let's

00:38:42.070 --> 00:38:44.840
say we know the stock
payoff at maturity.

00:38:44.840 --> 00:38:48.760
And what you do-- then the price
of derivative is very simple.

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:51.130
Essentially, you take the
average of this payoff,

00:38:51.130 --> 00:38:52.047
over the distribution.

00:38:52.047 --> 00:38:53.838
And you know distribution,
because you just

00:38:53.838 --> 00:38:55.060
simulated the stock price.

00:38:55.060 --> 00:39:00.249
And you just discount it
with the interest rate.

00:39:00.249 --> 00:39:01.290
So it's extremely simple.

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:04.720
So in principle,
implementing this--

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:07.850
I'd say if you have
package like MATLAB,

00:39:07.850 --> 00:39:11.290
it probably takes like
maybe one hour at most,

00:39:11.290 --> 00:39:17.840
implement let's say pricing
of Black-Scholes formula

00:39:17.840 --> 00:39:19.930
via a Monte Carlo simulation.

00:39:19.930 --> 00:39:22.930
So maybe if you have
time, you can try this

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:28.060
and see how your Monte
Carlo solution converges

00:39:28.060 --> 00:39:32.650
to the exact result which was
first obtained by Black-Scholes

00:39:32.650 --> 00:39:33.900
and Merton.

00:39:33.900 --> 00:39:37.420
So basically, this is a
super powerful framework,

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:39.560
which basically tells
us something like this.

00:39:39.560 --> 00:39:43.190
So it's not applicable
just to the stock prices,

00:39:43.190 --> 00:39:46.130
but it's also applicable to
interest rate derivatives,

00:39:46.130 --> 00:39:49.460
credit derivatives, and
foreign exchange derivatives,

00:39:49.460 --> 00:39:50.670
so on and so forth.

00:39:50.670 --> 00:39:52.190
Basically, the
idea is like this.

00:39:52.190 --> 00:39:55.280
You have some-- the
payoff of your derivative

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:57.600
depends on various
financial variables.

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:01.670
And you simply simulate all of
them in the risk-neutral world.

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:02.170
Right?

00:40:02.170 --> 00:40:05.810
So you simulate all
of them, and then you

00:40:05.810 --> 00:40:08.310
could calculate the
average of the payoff.

00:40:08.310 --> 00:40:09.582
And you just discount it.

00:40:09.582 --> 00:40:11.290
And that's how you
can price derivatives.

00:40:11.290 --> 00:40:16.340
So in principle, if you have
a flexible IT infrastructure,

00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:20.090
like a financial institution,
so you can implement it.

00:40:20.090 --> 00:40:23.910
And then you can price
pretty much everything.

00:40:23.910 --> 00:40:27.790
That's basically how
exotic derivatives

00:40:27.790 --> 00:40:33.310
are priced, whose prices
are not easy to obtain

00:40:33.310 --> 00:40:35.450
using analytical methods.

00:40:35.450 --> 00:40:41.970
Which is the case for a
large amount of derivatives.

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:44.570
So this is the
whole idea, right?

00:40:44.570 --> 00:40:50.270
So Monte Carlo simulation is
a very fundamental concept.

00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:53.700
So we do the simulation
in the risk-neutral world,

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:56.315
and there are certain rules
how to write these equations

00:40:56.315 --> 00:40:58.440
for different asset classes--
could be stock again,

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:01.500
could be foreign exchange,
could be credit, could be rates,

00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:02.250
whatever.

00:41:02.250 --> 00:41:07.530
And then you do some kind of
sampling, you find average,

00:41:07.530 --> 00:41:10.270
and then basically you are done.

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:11.970
So this is how it
works with the stock,

00:41:11.970 --> 00:41:15.390
and let me just explain
how to generalize

00:41:15.390 --> 00:41:18.030
all these ideas for the case
of interest rates and credit

00:41:18.030 --> 00:41:18.900
derivatives.

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:24.160
So and-- let me just start from
the very basics of the interest

00:41:24.160 --> 00:41:25.750
rate derivatives.

00:41:25.750 --> 00:41:31.490
So of course the whole
point of these derivatives

00:41:31.490 --> 00:41:39.700
is to allow financial
institutions or individuals

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:42.780
to manage their interest
rate risk better.

00:41:42.780 --> 00:41:49.060
So businesses need money
to run their business.

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:52.590
So big institutions,
big corporations,

00:41:52.590 --> 00:41:55.420
have billions, [INAUDIBLE]
hundreds of billions of dollars

00:41:55.420 --> 00:41:57.645
of debt, and they know
how to risk manage

00:41:57.645 --> 00:41:59.570
it, [INAUDIBLE] efficiently.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:04.474
And just to make money, and
not even necessarily financial

00:42:04.474 --> 00:42:05.015
institutions.

00:42:13.356 --> 00:42:14.730
So of course if
you borrow money,

00:42:14.730 --> 00:42:16.430
then you need to
pay some interest.

00:42:16.430 --> 00:42:18.429
So you can think about
interest rate derivatives

00:42:18.429 --> 00:42:21.620
as some kind of option on
the stochastic interest,

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:24.660
because let's say say today,
you can borrow money at 5%.

00:42:24.660 --> 00:42:27.340
But tomorrow, this
rate can change.

00:42:27.340 --> 00:42:33.800
So in order to control
this uncertainty,

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:38.470
you need to be able to
buy some derivatives,

00:42:38.470 --> 00:42:41.305
just to hedge your
exposure, for example.

00:42:41.305 --> 00:42:42.430
Or it might just speculate.

00:42:42.430 --> 00:42:45.040
Maybe you just have some view
that rates will go up or down.

00:42:45.040 --> 00:42:47.740
So it depends on the type
of investor or speculator,

00:42:47.740 --> 00:42:49.809
whatever.

00:42:49.809 --> 00:42:51.600
And so I mean this is
a very simple concept

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:52.880
of present value of money.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:55.290
If I have dollar
today, it's definitely

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:57.800
better than the dollar
one year from now.

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.130
Let's say I have
a dollar, right?

00:43:08.860 --> 00:43:11.610
But I will get it only
in one year from now.

00:43:11.610 --> 00:43:13.150
So how much does it cost?

00:43:13.150 --> 00:43:15.720
It's clear that if the
interest rate is 5%,

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:16.850
it roughly costs $0.95.

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:17.700
Right?

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:19.400
Because what do I do?

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:25.430
If the interest rate is
5%, then I take $0.95,

00:43:25.430 --> 00:43:28.510
and I'd put it into bank
account, and I'd make 5%.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:33.260
So I will get like $1
in one year from now.

00:43:33.260 --> 00:43:36.150
So there exists very important
concept of the present value.

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:39.740
Or like time value of money.

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:43.080
Depending on where
in the future you

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:47.480
are, how much money
it costs today.

00:43:47.480 --> 00:43:51.305
And people talk about-- it's
very often a fundamental notion

00:43:51.305 --> 00:43:55.100
of the fixed income derivative,
is the discount factor.

00:43:55.100 --> 00:43:57.290
So it essentially
tell you that OK,

00:43:57.290 --> 00:44:00.720
if you have one dollar
today, it costs one dollar.

00:44:00.720 --> 00:44:04.820
But if you have one
dollar in the future,

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:06.900
basically it costs
something else.

00:44:06.900 --> 00:44:14.640
So this is a very important
notion in finance.

00:44:14.640 --> 00:44:17.750
So I'll tell a little
bit more how [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:20.270
them together, this
functional [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:20.270 --> 00:44:23.740
So another very important
thing in the interest rate

00:44:23.740 --> 00:44:25.660
derivatives is the forward rate.

00:44:25.660 --> 00:44:27.917
So remember, okay, so
we have discount factor.

00:44:27.917 --> 00:44:30.000
And the very important
thing about discount factor

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:31.270
is it should start at 1.

00:44:31.270 --> 00:44:33.440
Because a dollar
today is a dollar.

00:44:33.440 --> 00:44:35.600
There is no uncertainty, right?

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:38.250
Thus it's clear
that this function

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:42.870
should be decaying, or at least
non-increasing, with time.

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:44.750
So that's why it's
very convenient

00:44:44.750 --> 00:44:51.600
to parametrize this kind of
function with forward rates.

00:44:51.600 --> 00:44:56.270
So this is some
positive forward rates.

00:44:56.270 --> 00:44:58.430
And [INAUDIBLE] very convenient.

00:44:58.430 --> 00:45:00.170
And remember, let's
say, in the example

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:09.500
below, like on this page,
if all maturities earn 5%,

00:45:09.500 --> 00:45:14.320
then this is simply 5% a year.

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:22.510
So for this example, basically
your forward rate is just flat.

00:45:22.510 --> 00:45:24.330
OK, so if this is an
example-- and when

00:45:24.330 --> 00:45:26.038
you talk about interest
rate derivatives,

00:45:26.038 --> 00:45:31.030
it's very convenient
to model the dynamics

00:45:31.030 --> 00:45:31.990
of the forward rates.

00:45:31.990 --> 00:45:38.690
So again, it's very
different from the stock,

00:45:38.690 --> 00:45:41.150
because it's got an
additional dimension.

00:45:41.150 --> 00:45:44.060
So if you model
the stock dynamics,

00:45:44.060 --> 00:45:45.170
it's just a point process.

00:45:45.170 --> 00:45:45.670
Right?

00:45:45.670 --> 00:45:49.710
Let's say it's $100 today,
and then you start modeling.

00:45:49.710 --> 00:45:53.620
Next, they'll go to $95, could
go to $105, so on and so forth.

00:45:53.620 --> 00:45:59.240
But interest rates,
it's more about curve.

00:45:59.240 --> 00:46:01.990
So it has an extra dimension--
it's a one-dimensional object.

00:46:01.990 --> 00:46:03.239
And the reason is very simple.

00:46:03.239 --> 00:46:06.340
In general, let's say if you
borrow money for one year,

00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:09.840
then let's say you
pay one percent.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:12.550
But if you borrow
for two years, it

00:46:12.550 --> 00:46:16.010
might be that you borrow
it for 2%, and so on.

00:46:16.010 --> 00:46:18.120
So there's a concept
of the yield curve.

00:46:18.120 --> 00:46:22.650
And here basically tells us how
much different maturities make.

00:46:22.650 --> 00:46:24.754
So in a typical situation,
with your curve,

00:46:24.754 --> 00:46:26.170
if you don't have
some [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:26.170 --> 00:46:28.524
of recession, which
sometimes happens,

00:46:28.524 --> 00:46:29.690
it's usually upward sloping.

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:33.170
This basically means if you
borrow money for longer term,

00:46:33.170 --> 00:46:34.730
you pay higher interest.

00:46:34.730 --> 00:46:36.430
You can see it very easily.

00:46:36.430 --> 00:46:38.750
Like for those who have
mortgages right there,

00:46:38.750 --> 00:46:45.460
it's always like 15-year
mortgage rate is lower

00:46:45.460 --> 00:46:48.660
than 30-year mortgage rate.

00:46:48.660 --> 00:46:51.369
And just here I just
show-- to give you

00:46:51.369 --> 00:46:53.910
a [INAUDIBLE], of where we are
right now in terms of interest

00:46:53.910 --> 00:47:01.127
rates, basically I just show
you the yield of a 10-year US

00:47:01.127 --> 00:47:01.710
Treasury note.

00:47:01.710 --> 00:47:03.360
So what is 10-year
Treasury note?

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:05.660
Basically, the US
government borrows money

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:07.320
to finance its activities.

00:47:07.320 --> 00:47:09.570
And then it works like this.

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:11.190
Let's say I'm an investor.

00:47:11.190 --> 00:47:13.860
I'm giving the US
government $100.

00:47:13.860 --> 00:47:17.440
And then every year, like
for the next 10 years--

00:47:17.440 --> 00:47:19.320
more exactly, like
twice a year--

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:22.460
let's say they are
paying me some coupon.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:26.360
Let's say if the interest
rate per year is 5%,

00:47:26.360 --> 00:47:29.490
this means that if I give
the US government $100,

00:47:29.490 --> 00:47:34.550
then the government pays
me $2.50 every half a year.

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:38.550
And at the very end,
in 10 years from now,

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:43.330
they must return
$100, the notional.

00:47:43.330 --> 00:47:46.500
And basically, if you look again
how stochastic the rates are

00:47:46.500 --> 00:47:48.120
right and what
kind of environment

00:47:48.120 --> 00:47:53.710
we are in right now, you can
see that over the last about 50

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:58.010
years, we see very
interesting picture.

00:47:58.010 --> 00:48:02.070
From about '60s
to about '80, '82,

00:48:02.070 --> 00:48:05.320
we can see a tremendous
increase in interest rates.

00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:09.290
And this is something which
looks very unbelievable right

00:48:09.290 --> 00:48:10.140
now.

00:48:10.140 --> 00:48:12.030
So this problem nowadays.

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:21.330
If one takes, let's
say a mortgage,

00:48:21.330 --> 00:48:25.790
now a 30-year mortgage is
maybe 4%, 4.5% nowadays.

00:48:25.790 --> 00:48:30.670
But let's say here,
about 30 years ago, it

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:33.140
was like a [INAUDIBLE] interest
rate-- very high inflation.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:35.780
And mortgage rates
were in double digits.

00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:37.940
It was not uncommon
to pay like 15%

00:48:37.940 --> 00:48:39.790
if you would take
mortgage somewhere here.

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:41.490
So the rates were increasing.

00:48:41.490 --> 00:48:44.520
