So they describe dynamics,
instantaneous dynamics,

01:02:57.480 --> 01:02:58.950
of this rate.

01:02:58.950 --> 01:03:02.270
So instead of modeling
the whole curve,

01:03:02.270 --> 01:03:06.570
you model only just this
short rate and so on.

01:03:06.570 --> 01:03:09.620
So some of these models
are particular case

01:03:09.620 --> 01:03:10.960
of the HJM model.

01:03:10.960 --> 01:03:12.350
Some of them are not.

01:03:12.350 --> 01:03:17.410
But just to mention.

01:03:17.410 --> 01:03:27.130
And basically the idea, then, of
the interest rate derivatives,

01:03:27.130 --> 01:03:30.870
for example, let's say I want
to price an option that in five

01:03:30.870 --> 01:03:33.080
years from now, I enter a
particular interest rate

01:03:33.080 --> 01:03:38.740
swap which pays 5% on the
fixed leg and receives LIBOR.

01:03:38.740 --> 01:03:44.180
So I need to model the
dynamic of future yields.

01:03:44.180 --> 01:03:49.050
And remember, it's a very
important thing that, again,

01:03:49.050 --> 01:03:57.710
because we have
the curve, now we

01:03:57.710 --> 01:04:00.090
have two different times here.

01:04:00.090 --> 01:04:02.620
For the stock derivatives, we
just basically write dynamics,

01:04:02.620 --> 01:04:04.320
d of S_t is equal to something.

01:04:04.320 --> 01:04:06.380
And t is just basically
instantaneous time.

01:04:06.380 --> 01:04:12.470
Here t stands for
instantaneous time.

01:04:12.470 --> 01:04:20.940
And T, capital T, stands
for the future time.

01:04:20.940 --> 01:04:21.560
Here.

01:04:21.560 --> 01:04:23.450
So essentially if
you're here, you're

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:26.459
looking at the forward
rate somewhere here.

01:04:26.459 --> 01:04:28.375
And then you basically
describe with dynamics.

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:34.030
I don't want to go into
details, but again,

01:04:34.030 --> 01:04:38.520
using this very fundamental
result in pricing theory

01:04:38.520 --> 01:04:45.510
like Ito's Lemma, you can derive
the equation for this drift.

01:04:45.510 --> 01:04:48.910
So the problem is it
turns out it's always

01:04:48.910 --> 01:04:51.090
the case in the Monte
Carlo simulation.

01:04:51.090 --> 01:04:55.290
So you [INAUDIBLE] some time
equation and you have drift

01:04:55.290 --> 01:04:56.980
and you have volatility.

01:04:56.980 --> 01:05:00.390
So it turns out that
this drift, the real time

01:05:00.390 --> 01:05:03.500
drift, because you hedge,
drops out of your equation.

01:05:03.500 --> 01:05:05.520
And it turns out that
for the interest rate,

01:05:05.520 --> 01:05:07.035
there is some complication.

01:05:07.035 --> 01:05:11.980
In the risk-neutral world, this
real-world drift [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:11.980 --> 01:05:16.160
by some equation which
depends on sigma.

01:05:16.160 --> 01:05:18.140
So if you do the
calculation, then you

01:05:18.140 --> 01:05:24.140
will see that in the
risk-neutral world,

01:05:24.140 --> 01:05:25.910
if you [INAUDIBLE]
of following form,

01:05:25.910 --> 01:05:28.150
which is some
non-local equation.

01:05:28.150 --> 01:05:29.500
But it is what it is.

01:05:29.500 --> 01:05:30.830
So it's very straightforward.

01:05:30.830 --> 01:05:34.750
I encourage you just to, if you
have time, to go through this

01:05:34.750 --> 01:05:38.740
and really understand
how it works.

01:05:38.740 --> 01:05:44.130
But now once we have this,
the model for interest rate

01:05:44.130 --> 01:05:46.450
derivatives is very simple.

01:05:46.450 --> 01:05:50.176
And remember that
in the stock world--

01:05:50.176 --> 01:05:54.872
let me go back just
to this equation.

01:05:54.872 --> 01:05:56.830
So we started from some
stochastic differential

01:05:56.830 --> 01:05:58.040
equation.

01:05:58.040 --> 01:06:00.890
And then we simulate
different paths.

01:06:00.890 --> 01:06:05.260
And then basically we
average over the pay-off

01:06:05.260 --> 01:06:08.170
here at maturity
of the derivative,

01:06:08.170 --> 01:06:10.990
when actually we do the payment.

01:06:10.990 --> 01:06:14.300
And here the situation
is very similar.

01:06:14.300 --> 01:06:19.090
So we have some
initial curve which we

01:06:19.090 --> 01:06:21.310
obtain from the market today.

01:06:21.310 --> 01:06:27.580
And this curve dynamics is
described by this equation.

01:06:27.580 --> 01:06:30.290
Then we have distribution
of this curve in the future,

01:06:30.290 --> 01:06:32.600
and then you can price
all kinds of derivatives.

01:06:32.600 --> 01:06:35.270
So again, it's a very
fundamental framework.

01:06:35.270 --> 01:06:37.060
So very general.

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:42.160
So once the curve and
the volatility are known,

01:06:42.160 --> 01:06:46.000
you simply run this simulation
and you get your pay-off.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:49.200
So basically that's
how it works.

01:06:53.860 --> 01:06:58.280
And now another example,
which is basically--

01:06:58.280 --> 01:07:04.190
of this HJM model, is
basically credit derivatives.

01:07:04.190 --> 01:07:07.220
So I don't have
much time, but just

01:07:07.220 --> 01:07:13.210
mention-- I'll go very
briefly what's going on.

01:07:13.210 --> 01:07:17.090
So if you give money
just to someone,

01:07:17.090 --> 01:07:19.630
like to the
corporations, then there

01:07:19.630 --> 01:07:24.510
is a probability that you
won't get your money back.

01:07:24.510 --> 01:07:27.255
So corporations issue
bonds, financial instruments

01:07:27.255 --> 01:07:28.460
to raise capital.

01:07:28.460 --> 01:07:31.110
It's, again, very similar
to the US treasuries.

01:07:31.110 --> 01:07:34.390
And so you give them $100 and
they pay you 5% &lt; every year.

01:07:34.390 --> 01:07:37.430
And then let's say in 10
years, if it's a 10 year bond,

01:07:37.430 --> 01:07:39.377
they are supposed to
give your money back.

01:07:39.377 --> 01:07:40.460
But this might not happen.

01:07:40.460 --> 01:07:43.340
Corporations default because
they make their own decisions.

01:07:43.340 --> 01:07:45.400
Like something went
wrong with economy,

01:07:45.400 --> 01:07:46.820
and so on and so forth.

01:07:46.820 --> 01:07:47.940
It happens.

01:07:47.940 --> 01:07:51.360
So there is some risk
which is indicated here.

01:07:51.360 --> 01:07:53.020
We just call it default risk.

01:07:53.020 --> 01:07:55.870
So corporations or
private individuals,

01:07:55.870 --> 01:08:00.710
they have a right to
default. So they can default.

01:08:00.710 --> 01:08:06.650
And this is reflected in
the coupons which they pay.

01:08:06.650 --> 01:08:09.910
So for the US government
at the end of 2012.

01:08:09.910 --> 01:08:15.210
A 10 year bond would
pay just 1.7% a year.

01:08:15.210 --> 01:08:18.000
Again, we are in extremely
low environment which

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:19.630
looks like almost nothing.

01:08:19.630 --> 01:08:26.069
And remember that even if
you're an investor and if you

01:08:26.069 --> 01:08:29.895
buy this bond, then you
get your 1% interest

01:08:29.895 --> 01:08:31.770
but then you need to
pay taxes on the profit.

01:08:31.770 --> 01:08:34.890
So the return is
really very small.

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:39.060
So then, of course, if
you're an investor, then OK.

01:08:39.060 --> 01:08:43.020
The US government securities
are assumed to be risk-free,

01:08:43.020 --> 01:08:44.819
so you won't be
able to lose money.

01:08:44.819 --> 01:08:47.859
So this is a very
important benchmark.

01:08:47.859 --> 01:08:50.365
But then you can buy
bonds of corporations.

01:08:50.365 --> 01:08:53.840
But, of course, to compensate
for possible default,

01:08:53.840 --> 01:08:56.460
they pay higher coupon.

01:08:56.460 --> 01:08:59.160
For example, at the end of
2012, Morgan Stanley bonds

01:08:59.160 --> 01:09:02.189
would pay around,
let's say 5% a year.

01:09:02.189 --> 01:09:03.140
Significantly higher.

01:09:07.394 --> 01:09:08.852
Some governments
are right now very

01:09:08.852 --> 01:09:11.210
close to default.
So some time ago,

01:09:11.210 --> 01:09:14.380
for example, when Morgan Stanley
bonds would pay 5% a year.

01:09:14.380 --> 01:09:17.560
But say, Greece bonds
would pay 25%, 30% a year.

01:09:17.560 --> 01:09:23.359
Because nobody knows what's
going to happen there.

01:09:23.359 --> 01:09:26.880
It's clear that the economy
is not in good shape

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:30.610
and it all depends
on the bailouts.

01:09:30.610 --> 01:09:32.939
Or these bailouts are
conditioned, for example,

01:09:32.939 --> 01:09:36.080
that the right
government-- if you'll

01:09:36.080 --> 01:09:38.429
be in power and the
[INAUDIBLE] is unclear.

01:09:38.429 --> 01:09:39.720
So there's lots of uncertainty.

01:09:44.670 --> 01:09:47.300
Such uncertainties, that's
why, essentially, the yield--

01:09:47.300 --> 01:09:50.689
investors tell you would
require very high yield.

01:09:50.689 --> 01:09:56.210
And in the credit derivatives,
the fundamental instrument,

01:09:56.210 --> 01:09:58.490
is credit default swap.

01:09:58.490 --> 01:10:03.340
So if you have a risky
bond, then in order

01:10:03.340 --> 01:10:07.500
to protect from default you
can go, let's say to a bank,

01:10:07.500 --> 01:10:09.160
and buy a credit default swap.

01:10:09.160 --> 01:10:11.000
It basically means
that if you hold

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:16.010
a bond and default happens, then
the seller of this protection

01:10:16.010 --> 01:10:17.780
will compensate
you for the loss.

01:10:17.780 --> 01:10:23.270
For example, let's say
you bought a bond at $100.

01:10:23.270 --> 01:10:26.330
And then, let's say, in one
year the corporation defaults.

01:10:26.330 --> 01:10:29.200
And then what happens
in this event?

01:10:29.200 --> 01:10:31.342
Then court.

01:10:31.342 --> 01:10:32.450
Court happens.

01:10:32.450 --> 01:10:35.710
And the judge decides how
much money is recovered.

01:10:35.710 --> 01:10:38.550
And this money is distributed
to the bond investors.

01:10:38.550 --> 01:10:41.530
They're first in the queue.

01:10:41.530 --> 01:10:46.930
And then if, let's say, $0.70
on the dollar were recovered,

01:10:46.930 --> 01:10:54.600
then the default swap will
pay you $32 which you lost.

01:10:54.600 --> 01:11:03.100
And very fundamental concept in
the world of credit derivatives

01:11:03.100 --> 01:11:07.580
is market implied
survival probability.

01:11:07.580 --> 01:11:12.990
So in principle,
credit default swaps

01:11:12.990 --> 01:11:15.570
are available for
different entities.

01:11:15.570 --> 01:11:16.830
Let's say like Morgan Stanley.

01:11:16.830 --> 01:11:19.360
It could be Verizon.

01:11:19.360 --> 01:11:21.580
Could be AT&amp;T and
so on and so forth.

01:11:23.860 --> 01:11:29.244
And [INAUDIBLE] require
different payments.

01:11:29.244 --> 01:11:30.910
For example, let's
say if credit default

01:11:30.910 --> 01:11:32.930
swap for Morgan
Stanley, probably

01:11:32.930 --> 01:11:36.020
is like 5 year maturity, you
pay around 100 basis points.

01:11:36.020 --> 01:11:39.140
And if there is
some-- like Greece,

01:11:39.140 --> 01:11:43.162
probably, you pay like 500,
maybe 1,000 basis points

01:11:43.162 --> 01:11:44.120
or something like this.

01:11:44.120 --> 01:11:46.000
So market differentiates.

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:52.360
And based on this, you can then
do a very simple calculation.

01:11:52.360 --> 01:12:00.060
And you consider, it's very
easy to come with a concept

01:12:00.060 --> 01:12:01.450
of the survival probability.

01:12:01.450 --> 01:12:07.580
Roughly speaking if, let's
say, default protection

01:12:07.580 --> 01:12:11.840
on some reference entity
is worth 1% a year.

01:12:11.840 --> 01:12:15.640
And then what do we see?

01:12:15.640 --> 01:12:18.940
Then with probability 99% a
year, you will get your money.

01:12:18.940 --> 01:12:23.350
If probability 1% per
year, you will get nothing.

01:12:23.350 --> 01:12:25.190
So you can think
about it like this.

01:12:25.190 --> 01:12:29.010
This means you can say
the probability to default

01:12:29.010 --> 01:12:33.200
is roughly 1% a
year, in this case.

01:12:33.200 --> 01:12:39.390
And then we could talk about
survival probabilities,

01:12:39.390 --> 01:12:40.960
which is basically
one [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:40.960 --> 01:12:43.240
default probability.

01:12:43.240 --> 01:12:45.994
And you can then come
up with the concept

01:12:45.994 --> 01:12:47.910
of survival probabilities,
which you can again

01:12:47.910 --> 01:12:53.530
parametrize with forward rates
which are called hazard rates.

01:12:53.530 --> 01:12:56.026
So credit derivatives,
in a sense,

01:12:56.026 --> 01:12:57.900
they're similar to
interest rate derivatives.

01:12:57.900 --> 01:13:00.260
Remember, in the case of
interest rate derivatives,

01:13:00.260 --> 01:13:04.250
we were talking about
discount factors.

01:13:04.250 --> 01:13:06.540
So this is like
the present value.

01:13:06.540 --> 01:13:08.419
Present value of money.

01:13:08.419 --> 01:13:10.710
In terms of world of credit
derivatives-- besides this,

01:13:10.710 --> 01:13:13.536
because of course
interest rates are also

01:13:13.536 --> 01:13:15.160
very important for
credit derivatives--

01:13:15.160 --> 01:13:17.110
we talk about
survival probability.

01:13:17.110 --> 01:13:21.030
Today it's equal to
1, but then it decays.

01:13:21.030 --> 01:13:23.530
And let's say if you
have a US government,

01:13:23.530 --> 01:13:25.670
basically it always stay at one.

01:13:25.670 --> 01:13:27.900
And let's say if it's
like Morgan Stanley,

01:13:27.900 --> 01:13:29.520
it goes like this.

01:13:29.520 --> 01:13:32.305
If it's some distressed
European sovereign,

01:13:32.305 --> 01:13:33.857
it will go like this.

01:13:33.857 --> 01:13:35.690
So basically it's
market-implied probability

01:13:35.690 --> 01:13:40.470
of default based on the
credit default swap market.

01:13:40.470 --> 01:13:44.060
And the idea of the HJM model
for the credit derivatives

01:13:44.060 --> 01:13:49.795
is that-- similar to the dynamic
of forward rates in interest

01:13:49.795 --> 01:13:54.320
rate case-- you simply describe
the dynamics of hazard rates

01:13:54.320 --> 01:13:58.300
which parametrize your
survival probabilities.

01:13:58.300 --> 01:14:05.040
And now let me see.

01:14:05.040 --> 01:14:09.390
Let me show an example of very
important type of derivatives,

01:14:09.390 --> 01:14:13.250
which are priced
using credit models.

01:14:13.250 --> 01:14:17.980
Let's talk about the
corporate callable bonds.

01:14:17.980 --> 01:14:25.880
So it's a very
simple instrument.

01:14:25.880 --> 01:14:27.240
Again, I'm a corporation.

01:14:27.240 --> 01:14:28.820
I borrow $100 from you.

01:14:28.820 --> 01:14:33.240
And let's say I'm paying
you 5% every year.

01:14:33.240 --> 01:14:39.040
But I have the
right at any time--

01:14:39.040 --> 01:14:45.460
or, let's say, once in three
months-- return you this $100,

01:14:45.460 --> 01:14:46.940
and basically close the deal.

01:14:46.940 --> 01:14:49.200
So why is that so valuable
for the corporations?

01:14:49.200 --> 01:14:51.470
Because today's
environment is such

01:14:51.470 --> 01:14:54.030
that I borrow at
a very high rate.

01:14:54.030 --> 01:14:58.320
In this example, let's
say I am paying 5% a year.

01:14:58.320 --> 01:15:03.770
And I issued a 10 year bond and
there's $100 million notional.

01:15:03.770 --> 01:15:06.400
So basically this means
that every year, I

01:15:06.400 --> 01:15:09.180
am paying to the investor 5%.

01:15:09.180 --> 01:15:10.640
$5 million.

01:15:10.640 --> 01:15:12.780
But let's say I'm paying 5%.

01:15:12.780 --> 01:15:14.800
I need this money to run
my business and so on.

01:15:14.800 --> 01:15:19.270
So it's some burden, but
usually all the corporations

01:15:19.270 --> 01:15:21.580
have significant amount of debt.

01:15:21.580 --> 01:15:24.620
So it's good to have debt if
you know how to manage it.

01:15:24.620 --> 01:15:27.530
Now let's say in three years
from now, situation changed.

01:15:27.530 --> 01:15:32.100
So now I can borrow
money for seven years,

01:15:32.100 --> 01:15:35.800
because initially I issued
the bond for 10 years.

01:15:35.800 --> 01:15:37.920
And now I have seven
years remaining,

01:15:37.920 --> 01:15:45.450
but it turns out I
can issue just a 3%.

01:15:45.450 --> 01:15:46.870
Basically this
means if I do this,

01:15:46.870 --> 01:15:51.980
if I exercise my call option,
then I will save 5 minus 3--

01:15:51.980 --> 01:15:55.690
2%-- times $100 million
times seven years.

01:15:55.690 --> 01:15:57.660
So it's $14 million.

01:15:57.660 --> 01:16:02.350
So that's kind of why callable
debt, it's good to issue it,

01:16:02.350 --> 01:16:04.414
because you can save money.

01:16:04.414 --> 01:16:06.580
It's very similar to what's
happening right now also

01:16:06.580 --> 01:16:08.670
for private individuals.

01:16:08.670 --> 01:16:13.760
Because in recent year
or couple of years,

01:16:13.760 --> 01:16:16.240
there was lot of refinancing
activity in the US.

01:16:16.240 --> 01:16:20.640
Remember rates are at
historical low right now.

01:16:20.640 --> 01:16:22.450
So rates are going
down, down, down.

01:16:22.450 --> 01:16:26.630
So let's say if you took
out a mortgage here at 6%,

01:16:26.630 --> 01:16:30.030
it was like you could
refinance at here, for example,

01:16:30.030 --> 01:16:31.170
the same mortgage.

01:16:31.170 --> 01:16:33.570
You could [INAUDIBLE]
like at 3.5%.

01:16:33.570 --> 01:16:36.630
So the same [INAUDIBLE] has
happened to corporations.

01:16:36.630 --> 01:16:44.330
So in the US, by default,
all mortgages are callable.

01:16:44.330 --> 01:16:46.330
And basically by
default, everybody

01:16:46.330 --> 01:16:48.010
has a right to refinance.

01:16:48.010 --> 01:16:50.330
So it's not like you
issue a 30 year bond

01:16:50.330 --> 01:16:53.010
and then even you're
paying a huge coupon,

01:16:53.010 --> 01:16:54.950
even you can refinance
lower percent-- which

01:16:54.950 --> 01:16:56.866
might be the case for
corporation, by the way.

01:16:56.866 --> 01:17:05.880
But by law in the US, all the
mortgages can be refinanced.

01:17:05.880 --> 01:17:07.130
So basically, that's the idea.

01:17:10.730 --> 01:17:16.882
So if you price this kind of
instrument as callable bond

01:17:16.882 --> 01:17:18.340
then you need to
take into account,

01:17:18.340 --> 01:17:23.380
of course, the interest
rate risk because you need

01:17:23.380 --> 01:17:26.770
to understand what is the
current level of interest rate

01:17:26.770 --> 01:17:27.840
you can charge.

01:17:27.840 --> 01:17:31.860
And also you need
to take into account

01:17:31.860 --> 01:17:35.060
the quality of the issuer.

01:17:35.060 --> 01:17:37.130
So if, let's say again, Greece.

01:17:37.130 --> 01:17:40.960
Or, let's say, Morgan
Stanley issue debt right now,

01:17:40.960 --> 01:17:47.060
then Morgan Stanley would
pay significantly less.

01:17:47.060 --> 01:17:50.030
It's all [INAUDIBLE]
on the fair market.

01:17:50.030 --> 01:17:51.950
[INAUDIBLE] result
and subsidies.

01:17:51.950 --> 01:17:54.870
And, of course, Morgan Stanley
would pay significantly less

01:17:54.870 --> 01:17:58.090
in the interest because
for the case of Greece,

01:17:58.090 --> 01:18:01.570
it is a much higher
default risk.

01:18:01.570 --> 01:18:06.750
And as I mentioned,
the idea is that you,

01:18:06.750 --> 01:18:11.500
in the world of
credit derivatives,

01:18:11.500 --> 01:18:14.400
there is the concept
of hazard rates

01:18:14.400 --> 01:18:19.500
which, again, some curve which
shows how risky the issuer is

01:18:19.500 --> 01:18:21.590
at some point in the future.

01:18:21.590 --> 01:18:27.110
And here I show the dynamics
for the forward rates,

01:18:27.110 --> 01:18:30.270
and here is the dynamics
of hazard rates.

01:18:30.270 --> 01:18:33.270
It shows you, basically,
how risky the issuer is.

01:18:33.270 --> 01:18:45.160
And then using similar
approach-- I show, give you

01:18:45.160 --> 01:18:47.610
as an exercise-- you
can prove again--

01:18:47.610 --> 01:18:53.030
it turns out if you know the
volatility of hazard rates,

01:18:53.030 --> 01:19:01.270
then you know how to simulate
the dynamics of hazard rates.

01:19:01.270 --> 01:19:06.300
So essentially, it's the
dynamics of all this.

01:19:06.300 --> 01:19:11.150
So again, it's the idea-- let
me go back just to the stock

01:19:11.150 --> 01:19:13.750
case-- again, it's the
idea, it's very simple.

01:19:13.750 --> 01:19:18.550
So you have all the
dynamic variables

01:19:18.550 --> 01:19:20.900
like rates and
[INAUDIBLE], in this case.

01:19:20.900 --> 01:19:24.100
Then what you do, you simulate
that in risk-neutral world.

01:19:24.100 --> 01:19:25.690
You have different path.

01:19:25.690 --> 01:19:27.760
And then you simply
average over the pay-off.

01:19:27.760 --> 01:19:32.449
So this is the beauty of
the risk-neutral pricing.

01:19:32.449 --> 01:19:34.865
There is a visual framework
which is basically implemented

01:19:34.865 --> 01:19:36.500
at all the major banks.

01:19:36.500 --> 01:19:39.890
Which is really like
the right approach

01:19:39.890 --> 01:19:42.010
to price very exotic
derivatives for which

01:19:42.010 --> 01:19:46.830
it's very hard to find the
exact analytical formulas.

01:19:46.830 --> 01:19:56.800
And let me show you one
example of securities

01:19:56.800 --> 01:20:00.400
which are issued by big banks.

01:20:00.400 --> 01:20:05.840
And that's where this HJM model
and Monte Carlo simulation

01:20:05.840 --> 01:20:08.612
are used all the time
because the pay-offs are

01:20:08.612 --> 01:20:09.320
very complicated.

01:20:12.550 --> 01:20:17.744
And example of such a product
is called structured note.

01:20:17.744 --> 01:20:18.910
So what's a structured note?

01:20:18.910 --> 01:20:27.480
It's-- again, corporations need
to raise money just to run this

01:20:27.480 --> 01:20:28.380
business.

01:20:28.380 --> 01:20:32.459
But, of course, I cannot
just get this money for free.

01:20:32.459 --> 01:20:33.625
I need to pay some interest.

01:20:36.460 --> 01:20:42.620
And again, if you look at
what happened last year.

01:20:42.620 --> 01:20:47.285
Again, at the end of last year,
for example a US 20 year bond

01:20:47.285 --> 01:20:49.260
would pay 1.7%.

01:20:49.260 --> 01:20:51.840
And if you also
pay all the taxes,

01:20:51.840 --> 01:20:56.050
then you probably get
something like 1.1%.

01:20:56.050 --> 01:20:58.010
And this might be even
lower than inflation.

01:20:58.010 --> 01:21:00.790
So investors, especially
long-term investors,

01:21:00.790 --> 01:21:04.730
they are not interested in
investing in the US treasuries

01:21:04.730 --> 01:21:10.240
because although it's risk
free, but there's no return.

01:21:10.240 --> 01:21:12.900
So you want to
generate some money.

01:21:12.900 --> 01:21:14.570
So what can you do, then?

01:21:14.570 --> 01:21:17.350
OK, so you don't want to
invest into treasuries.

01:21:17.350 --> 01:21:22.420
So then you can try to
find some corporate bonds.

01:21:22.420 --> 01:21:29.670
Again, corporates are risky
compared to the United States

01:21:29.670 --> 01:21:30.170
government.

01:21:34.720 --> 01:21:41.390
So typical coupon paid
by the corporate bonds

01:21:41.390 --> 01:21:42.920
would be higher.

01:21:42.920 --> 01:21:48.551
So let's say 5% for a
non-distressed typical US

01:21:48.551 --> 01:21:49.050
corporation.

01:21:52.170 --> 01:21:53.670
But again, 5%.

01:21:53.670 --> 01:22:00.380
Then you need to pay, let's
say, 30% tax top of this.

01:22:00.380 --> 01:22:02.290
So you're left 3.3%.

01:22:02.290 --> 01:22:05.660
There's inflation and
so on and so forth.

01:22:05.660 --> 01:22:09.380
So it still looks
like a low return.

01:22:09.380 --> 01:22:11.250
Of course,
[INAUDIBLE] below, you

01:22:11.250 --> 01:22:18.850
can buy some distressed bonds,
say from Greece or maybe

01:22:18.850 --> 01:22:21.690
from some distressed
corporations, which

01:22:21.690 --> 01:22:23.070
is a much higher.

01:22:23.070 --> 01:22:25.820
But it becomes
more like gambling.

01:22:28.720 --> 01:22:30.250
There's so much
uncertainties there,

01:22:30.250 --> 01:22:32.440
so it's more like you
can get very high return,

01:22:32.440 --> 01:22:39.040
but you can lose everything
because basically you're

01:22:39.040 --> 01:22:41.730
bearing very high credit risk.

01:22:41.730 --> 01:22:43.160
So what to do in this situation?

01:22:43.160 --> 01:22:48.110
Turns out that banks issue
very special securities called

01:22:48.110 --> 01:22:55.850
structured notes which are very
attractive to some investors.

01:22:55.850 --> 01:22:59.170
So let's say Morgan
Stanley-- but instead

01:22:59.170 --> 01:23:02.950
of issuing vanilla bond,
I am issuing-- and at 5%,

01:23:02.950 --> 01:23:07.720
let's say for 10 years-- I issue
a bond which pays 10% a year.

01:23:07.720 --> 01:23:08.860
So much higher coupon.

01:23:08.860 --> 01:23:13.800
But I pay you 10% only if
certain market conditions

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:15.290
are satisfied.

01:23:15.290 --> 01:23:18.770
So let's say market
condition like this.

01:23:18.770 --> 01:23:21.740
30 year swap rate is higher
than two year swap rate.

01:23:24.670 --> 01:23:29.230
Let's go back to the
picture which I drew.

01:23:29.230 --> 01:23:35.650
So essentially this means
that if you borrow money, then

01:23:35.650 --> 01:23:38.240
the short term borrowing
rate is smaller

01:23:38.240 --> 01:23:40.480
than the long term
borrowing rate, which

01:23:40.480 --> 01:23:42.420
usually is the case.

01:23:42.420 --> 01:23:45.820
So basically, let's assume
I pay you 10% percent

01:23:45.820 --> 01:23:47.580
if two conditions are satisfied.

01:23:47.580 --> 01:23:51.810
1% is the 30 year borrowing
rate in the economy right

01:23:51.810 --> 01:23:54.650
now is higher than
two year borrowing

01:23:54.650 --> 01:23:56.630
rate, which is this condition.

01:23:56.630 --> 01:23:58.520
Plus this second condition.

01:23:58.520 --> 01:24:01.210
S&amp;P 500 index is
higher than 880.

01:24:03.380 --> 01:24:08.430
So now if these
conditions are satisfied,

01:24:08.430 --> 01:24:11.320
then the investor will get 10%.

01:24:11.320 --> 01:24:13.190
If one of these
conditions breaks down,

01:24:13.190 --> 01:24:15.950
the investor would get nothing.

01:24:15.950 --> 01:24:17.570
So there are many
investors who would

01:24:17.570 --> 01:24:21.270
like to bear this kind
of risk because they

01:24:21.270 --> 01:24:26.870
have certain view on how
the economy would develop.

01:24:26.870 --> 01:24:29.600
Because right now, for
example, S&amp;P 500 index

01:24:29.600 --> 01:24:36.780
is pretty close to 2,000.

01:24:36.780 --> 01:24:39.990
So it's very unlikely
that it'll go down

01:24:39.990 --> 01:24:45.250
by the factor of
two, which is 880.

01:24:45.250 --> 01:24:46.920
So it's very low probability.

01:24:50.200 --> 01:24:53.570
And then also investor believes
that this will never happen.

01:24:53.570 --> 01:24:55.170
So we always will
be in the economy

01:24:55.170 --> 01:25:01.770
where it's still more
expensive to borrow long-term

01:25:01.770 --> 01:25:03.420
than short term.

01:25:03.420 --> 01:25:06.030
So in this case, it
turns out that the coupon

01:25:06.030 --> 01:25:07.290
can be enhanced.

01:25:07.290 --> 01:25:09.950
This is a whole idea
of the structured note.

01:25:09.950 --> 01:25:14.390
So instead of setting
like a plain coupon, 5%,

01:25:14.390 --> 01:25:17.190
I am selling [INAUDIBLE]
the derivative.

01:25:17.190 --> 01:25:19.810
And if investors like
it, it's kind of gambling

01:25:19.810 --> 01:25:23.870
but in educated
way because there's

01:25:23.870 --> 01:25:27.370
certain economic meaning
of these conditions.

01:25:27.370 --> 01:25:29.300
But this can get high return.

01:25:29.300 --> 01:25:35.319
And this is a very popular way
of financing because it turns

01:25:35.319 --> 01:25:37.610
out that investors are buying
this kind of instruments,

01:25:37.610 --> 01:25:38.651
but they are very unique.

01:25:41.927 --> 01:25:43.010
There's a lot very liquid.

01:25:43.010 --> 01:25:45.230
Therefore when issue
this kind of instrument,

01:25:45.230 --> 01:25:48.920
even if you price it correctly
using all the models,

01:25:48.920 --> 01:25:51.140
the bank or
financial institution

01:25:51.140 --> 01:25:55.570
which issues these instruments
can make some extra money.

01:25:55.570 --> 01:26:00.140
So effectively it's cheaper
to issue these instruments

01:26:00.140 --> 01:26:02.330
than to issue vanilla bonds.

01:26:02.330 --> 01:26:05.300
And all of these big banks,
they have all the machinery

01:26:05.300 --> 01:26:08.110
to risk manage this kind
of [INAUDIBLE] derivatives.

01:26:08.110 --> 01:26:11.070
So they know what
they are doing.

01:26:11.070 --> 01:26:13.160
So they sell this
kind of product,

01:26:13.160 --> 01:26:14.910
and they're hedging
their exposure.

01:26:14.910 --> 01:26:18.540
And they realize some
profit because you

01:26:18.540 --> 01:26:21.480
can't identify how much
[INAUDIBLE] instrument is.

01:26:21.480 --> 01:26:22.439
So it's good for banks.

01:26:22.439 --> 01:26:24.313
And it's also good for
investors because they

01:26:24.313 --> 01:26:26.360
are looking for this kind
of yield enhancement.

01:26:26.360 --> 01:26:29.400
They want to have
a higher yield.

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:31.600
And they are
taking-- and they're

01:26:31.600 --> 01:26:34.730
willing to take this risk.

01:26:34.730 --> 01:26:39.300
But again, it's an
educated risk because like,

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:41.310
this condition, for
example, here, they

01:26:41.310 --> 01:26:43.170
have a very clear
economical meaning.

01:26:43.170 --> 01:26:45.710
So if an investor
understands what's going on,

01:26:45.710 --> 01:26:48.889
then it's a reasonable risk.

01:26:48.889 --> 01:26:50.680
And, of course, what
do you do in this case

01:26:50.680 --> 01:26:52.450
if you want to model
something like this?

01:26:52.450 --> 01:26:55.510
Then it's very
complicated to find

01:26:55.510 --> 01:26:58.100
any kind of analytic
approximations

01:26:58.100 --> 01:27:00.360
here in the real world.

01:27:00.360 --> 01:27:02.120
So what do we do?

01:27:02.120 --> 01:27:04.560
We simulate the
stock market price.

01:27:04.560 --> 01:27:11.170
We simulate the 30 year
yield and 10 year yield.

01:27:11.170 --> 01:27:14.570
And we simulate Morgan
Stanley's credit spread.

01:27:14.570 --> 01:27:17.020
And we do it all simultaneously,
at the same time.

01:27:17.020 --> 01:27:20.620
And then we see in the
Monte Carlo simulation

01:27:20.620 --> 01:27:24.420
if this condition is satisfied
for every coupon date,

01:27:24.420 --> 01:27:27.140
then we're paying 10%.

01:27:27.140 --> 01:27:29.630
If something is broken,
then we are paying 0.

01:27:29.630 --> 01:27:31.660
So if we simulate many,
many paths like this

01:27:31.660 --> 01:27:34.920
and then we calculate
the average value of it.

01:27:34.920 --> 01:27:36.630
And then we come
up with the price

01:27:36.630 --> 01:27:39.520
and then we quote this
price to the investor.

01:27:39.520 --> 01:27:41.961
And again, I say, these
products are very nonstandard.

01:27:41.961 --> 01:27:42.460
That's fine.

01:27:42.460 --> 01:27:46.070
You can make some extra money.

01:27:46.070 --> 01:27:50.240
And as a firm, you
save money because it's

01:27:50.240 --> 01:27:53.420
cheaper than to issue
plain vanilla bonds.

01:27:53.420 --> 01:27:57.020
And just to give
you the idea where

01:27:57.020 --> 01:27:58.550
we are in terms of numbers.

01:27:58.550 --> 01:28:05.430
So here there is a
graph of difference

01:28:05.430 --> 01:28:08.600
between 30 year borrowing
rate and two year borrowing

01:28:08.600 --> 01:28:14.060
rate for the last decade.

01:28:14.060 --> 01:28:17.070
So you see, this
difference always positive.

01:28:17.070 --> 01:28:22.260
It was negative only very
shortly for some time

01:28:22.260 --> 01:28:25.640
around 2005, 2006.

01:28:25.640 --> 01:28:28.380
So it's very interesting thing.

01:28:28.380 --> 01:28:34.975
So when you price
derivative, then there's

01:28:34.975 --> 01:28:38.100
a notion of
market-implied numbers.

01:28:38.100 --> 01:28:42.235
It turns out if you look at
how different instruments are

01:28:42.235 --> 01:28:44.210
priced on the market,
then the probability--

01:28:47.320 --> 01:28:49.600
Then you can ask
a question: What

01:28:49.600 --> 01:28:56.200
is the probability
that this-- Let's

01:28:56.200 --> 01:29:00.530
say if I run, for example, this
stochastically for the last 10

01:29:00.530 --> 01:29:05.720
years, then how--
what the probability

01:29:05.720 --> 01:29:10.929
that this difference
is positive.

01:29:10.929 --> 01:29:12.637
And then it turns out
probability is only

01:29:12.637 --> 01:29:13.720
80% percent.

01:29:13.720 --> 01:29:18.010
Whereas in reality, it was
realized only for a few days.

01:29:18.010 --> 01:29:21.280
So it's significantly lower.

01:29:21.280 --> 01:29:24.420
So basically, then, the
investor says like this.

01:29:24.420 --> 01:29:27.810
So market give me the
discount, like 80%.

01:29:27.810 --> 01:29:30.950
But I know that this almost
never happen in the past.

01:29:30.950 --> 01:29:34.860
Therefore I believe that it
will not happen in the future.

01:29:34.860 --> 01:29:37.680
Maybe it will happen,
but I will still

01:29:37.680 --> 01:29:39.530
make some extra money
because of this.

01:29:39.530 --> 01:29:43.420
So basically we have [INAUDIBLE]
enhancement by a factor 1

01:29:43.420 --> 01:29:44.540
divided by 0.8.

01:29:44.540 --> 01:29:47.690
1.25%.

01:29:47.690 --> 01:29:49.830
Second thing is about S&amp;P 500.

01:29:49.830 --> 01:29:53.720
If you look at the history of
this index, which is basically

01:29:53.720 --> 01:29:56.960
the main US market
index, then you

01:29:56.960 --> 01:30:07.300
see that it was historically
above 880 level for 94 days out

01:30:07.300 --> 01:30:08.930
of 100 days.

01:30:08.930 --> 01:30:10.750
So very, very high probability.

01:30:10.750 --> 01:30:16.194
But the market implies this will
be the case only in 75% case.

01:30:16.194 --> 01:30:17.860
The credit investor
would say like this.

01:30:17.860 --> 01:30:22.890
OK, now S&amp;P 500 is around 1,800.

01:30:22.890 --> 01:30:26.340
So what the probability it's
going to drop below 880?

01:30:26.340 --> 01:30:27.890
Of course there is
some probability,

01:30:27.890 --> 01:30:30.360
but if it's going to
happen because it will mean

01:30:30.360 --> 01:30:32.570
a very serious
recession, and it looks

01:30:32.570 --> 01:30:34.640
like the economy is improving.

01:30:34.640 --> 01:30:36.880
The market might
drop down, but maybe

01:30:36.880 --> 01:30:40.890
to the level of 1,500, 1,400.

01:30:40.890 --> 01:30:42.130
But not that low.

01:30:42.130 --> 01:30:48.570
Therefore the investor believes
that he, by taking this risk,

01:30:48.570 --> 01:30:52.640
he will again get
a higher coupon.

01:30:52.640 --> 01:30:54.960
So [INAUDIBLE] very popular
instruments which are

01:30:54.960 --> 01:30:58.754
solely price by Monte Carlo
simulation, which-- we have

01:30:58.754 --> 01:30:59.920
big businesses, for example,

01:30:59.920 --> 01:31:04.200
like Morgan Stanley, whose
goal is to raise capital

01:31:04.200 --> 01:31:08.680
by selling these exotic
products and hedging them using

01:31:08.680 --> 01:31:11.170
the Monte Carlo framework.

01:31:11.170 --> 01:31:13.900
And if the interest rates
are crucial for dynamics,

01:31:13.900 --> 01:31:18.260
then we use the HJM model for
simulating interest rates.

01:31:18.260 --> 01:31:21.210
So that's everything
I wanted to tell you

01:31:21.210 --> 01:31:23.790
about today, so
thank you very much.

