01:31:38.310 --> 01:31:40.200
So, in reality.

01:31:40.200 --> 01:31:41.930
So here's what happens.

01:31:41.930 --> 01:31:48.140
So let's go to a very
simple case of stock prices.

01:31:48.140 --> 01:31:53.710
So again, r here basically
is just the borrowing rate.

01:31:53.710 --> 01:31:55.960
It's like, let's say, whatever
the bank account gives.

01:31:55.960 --> 01:31:56.960
Which is known.

01:31:56.960 --> 01:31:59.210
So the only parameter which
isn't known is volatility.

01:31:59.210 --> 01:32:04.170
So usually, you have
liquid stocks, for example.

01:32:04.170 --> 01:32:06.020
Like IBM, Apple.

01:32:06.020 --> 01:32:10.650
Then there are a lot
of derivatives traded,

01:32:10.650 --> 01:32:12.180
which are very liquid.

01:32:12.180 --> 01:32:18.902
This means that you can imply
this sigma from the price

01:32:18.902 --> 01:32:21.030
of liquid derivatives.

01:32:21.030 --> 01:32:24.630
Because you know, for example,
that this particular option--

01:32:24.630 --> 01:32:27.580
let's say today
Apple traded at 600--

01:32:27.580 --> 01:32:31.750
and you know that at the money
option, so option with a strike

01:32:31.750 --> 01:32:35.320
600, in one year now, for
example, it's worth whatever.

01:32:35.320 --> 01:32:37.250
Like $50, for example.

01:32:37.250 --> 01:32:40.420
By knowing this, you
can imply this sigma.

01:32:40.420 --> 01:32:42.170
So the whole idea is like this.

01:32:42.170 --> 01:32:45.540
So you take very liquid
derivatives, like standard call

01:32:45.540 --> 01:32:49.340
options, and you
imply this sigma.

01:32:49.340 --> 01:32:51.240
And then you use
this model to price

01:32:51.240 --> 01:32:53.561
really truly exotic derivatives,
which are not vitally

01:32:53.561 --> 01:32:54.060
available.

01:32:54.060 --> 01:32:55.393
That's how big banks make money.

01:32:55.393 --> 01:32:56.910
Because we know
how to price them.

01:32:56.910 --> 01:32:58.830
We have clients come in.

01:32:58.830 --> 01:33:03.060
And we see the prices of
very liquid instruments

01:33:03.060 --> 01:33:04.550
and we buy them to hedge.

01:33:04.550 --> 01:33:07.770
So very often what we do is
that we do some very complicated

01:33:07.770 --> 01:33:11.190
deal, but we have an
ability to off-load it

01:33:11.190 --> 01:33:14.514
into simpler contracts,
which we know how to price.

01:33:14.514 --> 01:33:15.180
That's the idea.

01:33:15.780 --> 01:33:18.470
And the same is true for
all the other derivatives,

01:33:18.470 --> 01:33:20.670
from credit derivatives or
[INAUDIBLE] derivatives.

01:33:20.670 --> 01:33:23.510
So you try to imply the
sigma from the market.

01:33:23.510 --> 01:33:26.280
If there is no way
to do this-- which

01:33:26.280 --> 01:33:29.424
is very often the case for
credit derivatives because

01:33:29.424 --> 01:33:31.090
for the credit
derivatives, credit vol--

01:33:31.090 --> 01:33:36.780
is not very liquid,
not liquidly traded.

01:33:36.780 --> 01:33:39.350
Then the best thing
that you can do

01:33:39.350 --> 01:33:42.450
is to take historical estimates.

01:33:42.450 --> 01:33:46.750
So we also do this.

01:33:46.750 --> 01:33:49.134
There is nothing else.

01:33:49.134 --> 01:33:49.990
Yeah.

