01:36:44.637 --> 01:36:49.710
AUDIENCE: So is the pricing
of these more exotic products

01:36:49.710 --> 01:36:52.030
totally reliant
upon Monte Carlo,

01:36:52.030 --> 01:36:54.240
or are there other techniques?

01:36:54.240 --> 01:36:57.090
DENIS GOROKHOV: I mean,
usually it's Monte Carlo.

01:36:57.090 --> 01:37:02.010
So there are some derivatives
where analytical approximations

01:37:02.010 --> 01:37:02.940
are available.

01:37:02.940 --> 01:37:06.880
For example, for
interest rate derivative.

01:37:06.880 --> 01:37:09.910
Swaps are like a very
simple linear product.

01:37:09.910 --> 01:37:12.170
To price them, you
need discount function.

01:37:12.170 --> 01:37:13.560
So it's just arithmetic.

01:37:13.560 --> 01:37:16.040
Of course, it's all done,
just simple arithmetic.

01:37:16.040 --> 01:37:18.630
For swaptions,
standard swaptions,

01:37:18.630 --> 01:37:20.690
there is a model
called SABR model which

01:37:20.690 --> 01:37:22.670
allows some kind of
semi-analytical solutions,

01:37:22.670 --> 01:37:25.900
which are approximate
but of high quality.

01:37:25.900 --> 01:37:27.140
Then you can do it.

01:37:27.140 --> 01:37:29.170
But there are different
schools of thought.

01:37:29.170 --> 01:37:32.380
Because with some
approximations,

01:37:32.380 --> 01:37:35.070
which might fail for some
if maturity is very long,

01:37:35.070 --> 01:37:38.430
or it's very-- very deep
out of the money option.

01:37:38.430 --> 01:37:43.120
So very often what traders do,
even if their official numbers

01:37:43.120 --> 01:37:47.520
are only-- more simplified
models which kind of has

01:37:47.520 --> 01:37:50.150
some formula, they still round
the Monte Carlo simulation

01:37:50.150 --> 01:37:52.260
for the whole
portfolio to understand

01:37:52.260 --> 01:37:56.994
what the most complicated
model, like in terms

01:37:56.994 --> 01:37:58.660
of your present value
of your portfolio,

01:37:58.660 --> 01:38:00.182
in terms of the risk.

01:38:00.182 --> 01:38:01.640
But, of course,
this kind of double

01:38:01.640 --> 01:38:04.730
range accruals, which
are just [INAUDIBLE].

01:38:04.730 --> 01:38:07.240
It's impossible to build any
meaningful analytical model.

01:38:07.240 --> 01:38:11.230
You can do something,
but you won't

01:38:11.230 --> 01:38:12.540
be able to be competitive.

01:38:12.540 --> 01:38:16.392
It's just all Monte
Carlo simulation.

01:38:16.392 --> 01:38:19.380
AUDIENCE: So you said
usually this whole simulation

01:38:19.380 --> 01:38:22.190
process takes an hour
on a MATLAB program?

01:38:24.389 --> 01:38:25.180
DENIS GOROKHOV: No.

01:38:25.180 --> 01:38:26.040
No.

01:38:26.040 --> 01:38:27.770
It takes probably
like one hour just

01:38:27.770 --> 01:38:30.580
to write the whole program,
because it's very simple.

01:38:30.580 --> 01:38:33.450
So what you do, you
have Brownian motion.

01:38:33.450 --> 01:38:34.260
But what you do.

01:38:34.260 --> 01:38:36.170
MATLAB generates
Brownian motion.

01:38:36.170 --> 01:38:37.660
So you just do it.

01:38:37.660 --> 01:38:41.060
And then you write the
change in your price

01:38:41.060 --> 01:38:43.470
is equal to your
drift, which you know,

01:38:43.470 --> 01:38:44.720
plus some random number.

01:38:44.720 --> 01:38:47.510
And you basically just
simulate different path.

01:38:47.510 --> 01:38:49.600
And then if you
price a call option,

01:38:49.600 --> 01:38:54.920
you know the distribution
of your stock prices,

01:38:54.920 --> 01:38:56.920
let's say, in one year
from now with maturities.

01:38:56.920 --> 01:38:57.919
And you just do average.

01:38:57.919 --> 01:39:00.270
So it might take
someone 15 minutes

01:39:00.270 --> 01:39:01.910
to write this kind of program.

01:39:01.910 --> 01:39:05.350
This is so you can verify
numerically the accuracy

01:39:05.350 --> 01:39:08.810
of the-- verify numerically
Black-Scholes formula,

01:39:08.810 --> 01:39:09.750
for example.

01:39:09.750 --> 01:39:11.745
But the idea fits
very simple here.

01:39:11.745 --> 01:39:13.620
But, of course, for
these complicated models,

01:39:13.620 --> 01:39:16.920
which you-- for term
structure process like HJM,

01:39:16.920 --> 01:39:19.890
because it's already
one-dimensional object.

01:39:19.890 --> 01:39:23.070
And, of course, it's
much more complicated

01:39:23.070 --> 01:39:26.200
because besides
pricing, you need

01:39:26.200 --> 01:39:28.400
to have this idea of
calibration as you mentioned,

01:39:28.400 --> 01:39:32.180
because these volatilities are
not just usually historical.

01:39:32.180 --> 01:39:34.467
They're implied from
other instruments.

01:39:34.467 --> 01:39:36.050
So what you do in
practice, like this.

01:39:36.050 --> 01:39:38.510
So if you have liquid
instruments, liquid options,

01:39:38.510 --> 01:39:40.370
you have the model.

01:39:40.370 --> 01:39:42.210
But the model has
unknown parameters.

01:39:42.210 --> 01:39:43.890
First, we do the calibration.

01:39:43.890 --> 01:39:45.870
So we make sure that
our model prices all

01:39:45.870 --> 01:39:47.260
the simple instruments.

01:39:47.260 --> 01:39:49.950
And then we take the
derivative whose price

01:39:49.950 --> 01:39:55.660
is unknown because it's just
something very complicated.

01:39:55.660 --> 01:39:57.580
And then we just price
it, but our model's

01:39:57.580 --> 01:39:59.180
calibrated to
simple derivatives.

01:39:59.180 --> 01:40:01.510
And this tells us--
then this model,

01:40:01.510 --> 01:40:04.290
after pricing it and
running sensitivity

01:40:04.290 --> 01:40:05.730
with respect to
market parameters,

01:40:05.730 --> 01:40:08.580
tells us how to hedge it.

01:40:08.580 --> 01:40:11.149
That's the idea.

01:40:11.149 --> 01:40:12.940
AUDIENCE: You ought to
do post-hoc analyses

01:40:12.940 --> 01:40:17.615
to see how the models did in
the past so you can adjust them.

01:40:17.615 --> 01:40:18.490
DENIS GOROKHOV: Yeah.

01:40:18.490 --> 01:40:19.556
Yeah.

01:40:19.556 --> 01:40:21.722
AUDIENCE: Is that a big
part of what you have to do?

01:40:25.874 --> 01:40:27.540
DENIS GOROKHOV: I
will say in general we

01:40:27.540 --> 01:40:29.110
are moving to this direction.

01:40:29.110 --> 01:40:35.020
In general, of course, for Monte
Carlo-- from the [INAUDIBLE]

01:40:35.020 --> 01:40:37.630
point of view for complicated
Monte Carlo model,

01:40:37.630 --> 01:40:40.070
it's very difficult
to do technically.

01:40:40.070 --> 01:40:42.500
It's very difficult.
But if you do it,

01:40:42.500 --> 01:40:46.240
you cannot afford simple models
like for swaps and so on.

01:40:46.240 --> 01:40:47.674
AUDIENCE: --historical
experience

01:40:47.674 --> 01:40:50.439
with the projection
that you made.

01:40:50.439 --> 01:40:51.230
DENIS GOROKHOV: No.

01:40:51.230 --> 01:40:53.160
But the situation,
it's very different.

01:40:53.160 --> 01:40:55.730
So we don't make any
predictions here, remember.

01:40:55.730 --> 01:40:57.090
It's risk-neutral pricing.

01:40:57.090 --> 01:40:58.980
Just no prediction here.

01:40:58.980 --> 01:41:01.460
What we do here is like this.

01:41:04.300 --> 01:41:07.110
If we are a bank
and we want to trade

01:41:07.110 --> 01:41:09.110
all kinds of very
exotic derivatives

01:41:09.110 --> 01:41:13.440
which nobody knows
how to price but

01:41:13.440 --> 01:41:16.910
we have clients who want to buy
them with different reasons.

01:41:16.910 --> 01:41:19.170
Might want to
speculate or they want

01:41:19.170 --> 01:41:23.650
to manage their risk exposure
and so on and so forth.

01:41:23.650 --> 01:41:26.990
So nobody knows except
for like 10, 20 banks,

01:41:26.990 --> 01:41:27.740
how to price them.

01:41:27.740 --> 01:41:29.345
Because this is like, you
need to have infrastructure.

01:41:29.345 --> 01:41:31.160
You need to know how to do this.

01:41:31.160 --> 01:41:34.070
Then you need to have
some business channels,

01:41:34.070 --> 01:41:35.500
how to off-load this risk.

01:41:35.500 --> 01:41:38.110
So this is some very
exotic products.

01:41:38.110 --> 01:41:41.330
So now the idea of dynamic
hedging is like this.

01:41:41.330 --> 01:41:43.520
Remember, in the case
of Black-Scholes.

01:41:47.440 --> 01:41:51.480
You buy an option
and then you hedge it

01:41:51.480 --> 01:41:54.240
by holding a certain
amount of the underlying.

01:41:54.240 --> 01:41:56.120
So you don't make any money.

01:41:56.120 --> 01:42:04.170
But you want to make sure that
whatever happens to the market,

01:42:04.170 --> 01:42:05.110
you're fully hedged.

01:42:05.110 --> 01:42:07.680
So the market moves here,
you don't make any money.

01:42:07.680 --> 01:42:13.070
The market moves down,
you don't make any money.

01:42:13.070 --> 01:42:16.210
So the way how you make money
in this situation, basically

01:42:16.210 --> 01:42:20.930
this Black-Scholes formula,
in this case, the price which

01:42:20.930 --> 01:42:24.740
you charge for the
option is the price

01:42:24.740 --> 01:42:26.560
of executing the
hedging strategy.

01:42:26.560 --> 01:42:28.500
So if you charge
a little bit more,

01:42:28.500 --> 01:42:31.850
this is extra money
which you can make.

01:42:31.850 --> 01:42:32.980
So it's very different.

01:42:32.980 --> 01:42:36.500
So what you just mentioned
is like proprietary business.

01:42:36.500 --> 01:42:39.710
Big banks, they are not
supposed to do this.

01:42:39.710 --> 01:42:41.944
It's more like a
hedge fund world.

01:42:41.944 --> 01:42:42.860
Very different models.

01:42:42.860 --> 01:42:48.220
What we do, we try to manage
big portfolios of derivatives,

01:42:48.220 --> 01:42:50.010
all kinds of derivatives.

01:42:50.010 --> 01:42:56.010
And we try to price them and
charge a little bit extra so

01:42:56.010 --> 01:42:57.510
that we can make our living.

01:42:57.510 --> 01:43:00.420
But on the other hand,
we don't take any risk.

01:43:00.420 --> 01:43:02.300
That's the idea.

01:43:02.300 --> 01:43:04.170
[INAUDIBLE] just models.

01:43:04.170 --> 01:43:07.090
So from point of view in
terms of testing historically,

01:43:07.090 --> 01:43:08.470
you can still ask a question.

01:43:08.470 --> 01:43:13.930
Let's say if I go back 10 years.

01:43:13.930 --> 01:43:16.080
And let's say 10 years
ago, I would sell,

01:43:16.080 --> 01:43:18.840
for example, this stock option.

01:43:18.840 --> 01:43:22.320
And for the next 10 years,
using historical data,

01:43:22.320 --> 01:43:26.170
I see basically
how-- my model then

01:43:26.170 --> 01:43:29.790
tells me what my Greeks or
like what my sensitivity

01:43:29.790 --> 01:43:32.716
with respect to the
underlying-- what

01:43:32.716 --> 01:43:34.590
my sensitivity with
respect to underlying is.

01:43:34.590 --> 01:43:36.860
And then you can ask a question.

01:43:36.860 --> 01:43:40.950
How was this delta H
performing historically?

01:43:40.950 --> 01:43:44.730
Which is a reasonable
question because maybe you

01:43:44.730 --> 01:43:47.730
assume that the model
pretty much continuous.

01:43:47.730 --> 01:43:50.110
But maybe if your
dynamics is very jerky,

01:43:50.110 --> 01:43:53.120
then you can just lose money
because you just don't take

01:43:53.120 --> 01:43:55.030
into account these effects.

01:43:55.030 --> 01:43:57.494
This is an example of historical
analysis which we may run,

01:43:57.494 --> 01:43:59.410
but it has nothing to
do with prediction here.

01:43:59.410 --> 01:44:00.743
So it's a whole different world.

01:44:00.743 --> 01:44:02.480
So it's risk-neutral pricing.

01:44:02.480 --> 01:44:03.680
So we don't take any risk.

01:44:03.680 --> 01:44:04.751
That's the whole idea.

01:44:04.751 --> 01:44:07.000
But due to the fact that
derivatives are very complex,

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:12.690
even in this case, still
banks bear some residual risk,

01:44:12.690 --> 01:44:16.430
because remember we cannot
exactly off-load it, the risk.

01:44:16.430 --> 01:44:19.730
So we still have
some assumptions

01:44:19.730 --> 01:44:22.520
that we can re-balance our
position dynamically and move

01:44:22.520 --> 01:44:25.820
forward, basically,
and not lose money.

01:44:25.820 --> 01:44:28.206
That's the idea of it.

01:44:28.206 --> 01:44:33.970
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about the Monte Carlo pricing.

01:44:33.970 --> 01:44:37.460
You can set up the Monte
Carlo using implied parameters

01:44:37.460 --> 01:44:39.685
from current prices
of various derivatives

01:44:39.685 --> 01:44:43.672
in the market, which gives
you a good baseline price.

01:44:43.672 --> 01:44:46.395
I'm wondering what
other Monte Carlos

01:44:46.395 --> 01:44:53.200
do you do to have a robust
estimate of pricing, hedging

01:44:53.200 --> 01:44:55.690
cost.

01:44:55.690 --> 01:44:58.310
I would think that there
would be, I don't know,

01:44:58.310 --> 01:45:04.846
maybe some stress scenarios
in the market or alternatives.

01:45:04.846 --> 01:45:08.480
You probably don't
just do one Monte Carlo

01:45:08.480 --> 01:45:10.850
study with current parameters.

01:45:10.850 --> 01:45:13.040
You probably have
different sets.

01:45:13.040 --> 01:45:15.950
And I'm wondering how
extensive is that?

01:45:17.255 --> 01:45:18.380
DENIS GOROKHOV: Absolutely.

01:45:18.380 --> 01:45:18.963
You are right.

01:45:18.963 --> 01:45:21.020
So if you just do
the Monte Carlo,

01:45:21.020 --> 01:45:23.140
then you just know the price.

01:45:23.140 --> 01:45:27.115
But price is nothing,
because dynamic hedging,

01:45:27.115 --> 01:45:28.490
all this business
of derivatives,

01:45:28.490 --> 01:45:30.550
it's not just about how
much it's right now,

01:45:30.550 --> 01:45:33.380
but what to do if the
market behaves this way.

01:45:33.380 --> 01:45:36.120
So of course you could
collate all your Greeks.

01:45:36.120 --> 01:45:37.140
That's very important.

01:45:37.140 --> 01:45:41.160
But Greeks is like,
say, your delta.

01:45:41.160 --> 01:45:42.340
It's all about linear terms.

01:45:42.340 --> 01:45:44.460
So of course it's a
very important thing.

01:45:44.460 --> 01:45:46.160
What happen to the
portfolio, let's

01:45:46.160 --> 01:45:48.960
say, if there is a very
sharp, for example,

01:45:48.960 --> 01:45:50.180
jump in interest rate.

01:45:50.180 --> 01:45:55.950
So let's say, what happens
if rates jump forward by 1%.

01:45:55.950 --> 01:45:57.590
Or if they jump down.

01:45:57.590 --> 01:46:02.390
What happens if volatility
in a particular time,

01:46:02.390 --> 01:46:04.320
region, for example, blows up.

01:46:04.320 --> 01:46:06.040
You run all these
kind of analyses.

01:46:06.040 --> 01:46:09.380
So it's big departments
at the banks who

01:46:09.380 --> 01:46:10.685
look at all this kind of risks.

01:46:10.685 --> 01:46:15.919
So it all comes to
one business unit

01:46:15.919 --> 01:46:17.710
which looks all kinds
of risks of the firm.

01:46:20.490 --> 01:46:27.150
It's a very big
thing for the bank.

01:46:27.150 --> 01:46:29.190
This notion of stress test.

01:46:29.190 --> 01:46:31.780
Basically right now,
all of the banks

01:46:31.780 --> 01:46:33.980
are very heavily regulated
by the government.

01:46:33.980 --> 01:46:36.210
So the government can
tell us what happens.

01:46:36.210 --> 01:46:38.060
For example, for
the whole bank--

01:46:38.060 --> 01:46:40.477
not just for a particular
desk which trades,

01:46:40.477 --> 01:46:41.310
whatever, swaptions.

01:46:41.310 --> 01:46:44.800
What happens to all your bank,
to all kinds of cash flows

01:46:44.800 --> 01:46:46.430
which you can have
if, let's say,

01:46:46.430 --> 01:46:49.110
interest rates jump
by 100% percent.

01:46:49.110 --> 01:46:54.870
We have a huge group of people,
quants, IT, risk managers,

01:46:54.870 --> 01:46:56.870
who are looking at all
these numbers trying

01:46:56.870 --> 01:46:57.900
to understand it.

01:46:57.900 --> 01:47:02.340
And for a big bank, very
non-trivial problem, actually.

